{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Trinidad and Tobago", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in the Republic of Trinidad and Tobago}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Trinidad and Tobago\n| first_case      = [[Trinidad and Tobago]]\n| total_ili       = \n| suspected_cases = \n| confirmed_cases = 115<ref name=\"trinidad-21april\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.health.gov.tt/sitepages/default.aspx?id=293 |title=Covid-19 (Novel Coronavirus) |access-date=21 April 2020 |website=health.gov.tt}}</ref> (2020-04-21)\n| recovery_cases  = 28<ref name=\"trinidad-21april\"/>\n| deaths          = 8<ref name=\"trinidad-21april\"/>\n| origin          = [[Wuhan, China]]\n| arrival_date    = 12 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=12|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| location        = [[Trinidad and Tobago]]\n| map1            = \n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| legend3         = \n| map3            = \n| legend2         = \n| map2            = \n| legend1         = \n| website         = [http://www.health.gov.tt health.gov.tt]\n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached the [[Republic of Trinidad and Tobago]] in March 2020.\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]],<ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |last= |first= |date= |website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/>\n\n== Timeline ==\n===March 2020===\nOn 12 March, the Republic of Trinidad and Tobago recorded its first case of COVID-19. It was a 52-year-old man who had recently been to [[Switzerland]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://dominicanewsonline.com/news/homepage/news/trinidad-tobago-confirms-first-case-of-coronavirus-covid-19/ |title = Trinidad & Tobago confirms first case of coronavirus (COVID - 19) |work=Dominica News Online |date = 13 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.looptt.com/content/moh-announces-tt-has-one-case-covid-19|title=MOH: One case of COVID-19 confirmed in T&T|website=looptt.com|language=en|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/latestnews/Trinidad_records_first_case_of_coronavirus|title=Jamaica Observer Limited|website=Jamaica Observer|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.guardian.co.tt/news/tt-gets-first-case-of-coronavirus-covid19-6.2.1077775.1564a3d6e9|title=T&T gets first case of coronavirus COVID-19|last=Nanton|first=Sampson|date=12 March 2020|website=Trinidad and Tobago Guardian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://trinidadexpress.com/newsextra/t-t-confirms-first-case-of-coronavirus/article_5c05b35a-6495-11ea-8bd4-1bba999d27a3.html|title=T&T confirms first case of coronavirus|website=Trinidad Express Newspapers|language=en|access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref> He was self-isolated before he began experiencing symptoms of COVID-19. Contact tracing for the passengers of the patient's flight is being conducted.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nOn 13 March, a second case of COVID-19 was recorded by Trinidad and Tobago.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://trinidadexpress.com/newsextra/t-t-records-nd-case-of-covid/article_dbd560e6-6592-11ea-adf9-9b60cb64b6db.html |title = T&T records 2nd case of COVID-19 |work=Daily Express |date=13 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://globalvoices.org/2020/03/14/trinidad-tobago-clamps-down-as-two-cases-of-covid-19-confirmed/ | title=Trinidad & Tobago clamps down as two cases of COVID-19 are confirmed |work= Global Voices| date=14 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.guardian.co.tt/news/second-covid19-case-confirmed-6.2.1078784.1b403b46dd |title = Second COVID-19 case confirmed }}</ref> The patient, a 66-year-old male with an unknown travel history, presented himself at a health facility and was soon isolated. Others who may have been exposed to the patient are also being quarantined.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.looptt.com/content/ministry-health-confirms-second-case-covid-19-tt|title=Ministry of Health confirms second case of COVID-19 in T&T|website=looptt.com|language=en|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.stabroeknews.com/2020/03/15/news/regional/trinidad/66-year-old-man-is-trinidad-tobagos-second-covid-19-case/ | title=66-year-old man is Trinidad & Tobago's second COVID-19 case |work=Starbroek News | date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.guardian.co.tt/news/tt-now-up-to-4-covid19-cases-6.2.1079739.e6882b3e89 |title = T&T now up to 4 COVID-19 cases |work=Trinidad & Tobago Guardian |access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://wired868.com/2020/03/13/sixty-six-year-old-man-confirmed-as-trinidads-second-covid-19-case/ | title=Sixty-six year old man confirmed as Trinidad's second Covid-19 case |work=Wired868.com | date=14 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nTwo more cases were confirmed on the night of 15 March, bringing the total to 4 cases.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.looptt.com/content/moh-confirms-two-more-covid-19-cases-tt | title=MOH confirms two more COVID-19 cases in T&T |work=looptt.com |date=15 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/trinidad-and-tobago-now-has-4-confirmed-coronavirus-disease-covid-19-patients/ |title = Trinidad and Tobago now has 4 confirmed coronavirus COVID-19 patients |work=St. Lucia News Online |date = 16 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://trinidadexpress.com/newsextra/t-t-now-has-confirmed-covid--victims/article_b3eb4662-6728-11ea-a920-0b96b8307903.html |title = T&T now has 4 confirmed COVID-19 victims}}</ref> A fifth case was confirmed on 16 March.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://trinidadexpress.com/newsextra/t-t-confirms-th-covid--victim/article_48e13c62-67e8-11ea-ba35-8b36de2e2dd9.html | title=T&T confirms 5th COVID-19 victim}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.stabroeknews.com/2020/03/17/news/regional/trinidad/trinidad-confirms-5th-coronavirus-case/ | title=Trinidad confirms 5th coronavirus case| date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.guardian.co.tt/news/5th-tt-covid19-case-confirmed-6.2.1080515.439cfd44ef |title = 5th T&T COVID-19 case confirmed}}</ref> On 17 March, another two cases were confirmed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://trinidadexpress.com/newsextra/t-t-now-has-confirmed-covid--cases/article_25ca5eb6-68c4-11ea-9d56-0f5f6a3983f8.html|title=T&T now has 7 confirmed COVID-19 cases|website=Trinidad Express Newspapers|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/trinidad-and-tobago-now-has-7-confirmed-coronavirus-covid-19-cases/|title=Trinidad and Tobago now has 7 confirmed coronavirus-COVID-19 cases|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref> Another two cases were confirmed on 19 March.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://trinidadexpress.com/news/t-t-now-has-cases-of-covid/article_2d9b004e-69c5-11ea-a498-5b9a526e67c6.html |title = T&T now has 9 cases of COVID-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.guardian.co.tt/news/tt-covid19-cases-now-up-to-9-6.2.1082264.95a5c787ac |title = T&T COVID-19 cases now up to 9}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.looptt.com/content/moh-reports-two-new-cases-covid-19 |title = MOH reports two new cases of COVID-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/trinidad-tobago-now-at-9-confirmed-covid-19-cases/ | title=Trinidad & Tobago now at 9 confirmed COVID-19 cases| date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, 40 more cases were confirmed. Sixty eight (68) nationals left for a 7-day cruise on the Caribbean sea on 5 March. After a suspected outbreak of COVID-19 on board, the Costa Favolosa was forced to anchor off the coast of Guadeloupe for several days. The nationals returned to Trinidad and Tobago on 17 March via a chartered flight from Guadeloupe. They were immediately screened and tested at Piarco International Airport and later taken to a quarantine facility. On 21 March it was confirmed that 40 of the 68 persons that were quarantined tested positive for COVID-19, bringing the total number of confirmed cases to 49.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guardian.co.tt/news/68-trinis-back-from-illfated-cruise-quarantined-in-balandra-6.2.1082228.4a205ffd90|title=68 Trinis back from ill-fated cruise quarantined in Balandra}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guardian.co.tt/news/40-new-covid19-cases-hospitalised-at-couva-6.2.1083879.9e92dd5f7d#.XnYtirdvus|title= 40 new COVID-19 cases hospitalised at Couva}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://trinidadexpress.com/news/local/anxiety-over-stranded-trinis/article_d2215fb8-68bd-11ea-8b3b-2b1f2d45ce34.html|title=Anxiety over stranded trinis}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, COVID-19 claimed its first victim in Trinidad.\nHe was a seventy-seven-year-old male with known pre-existing medical conditions.\n\nOn 26 March, the second reported COVID-19 death was an eighty-year-old male with pre-existing medical conditions. He was among the rescued cruise ship passengers quarantined at Camp Balandra.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://trinidadexpress.com/newsextra/t-t-records-nd-covid--death/article_19988bb0-7038-11ea-a9cf-6f836c8eabc2.html|title=T&T records 2nd COVID-19 death|website=Trinidad Express Newspapers|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> The Ministry of Health also reported that one of the patients who tested positive, was quarantined and treated has since been discharged.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsday.co.tt/2020/03/27/2nd-local-covid19-death-confirmed/|title=2nd local covid19 death confirmed|date=2020-03-27|website=Trinidad and Tobago Newsday|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\n=== April 2020 ===\nOn 5 April, Tobago recorded its first death, an elderly male with pre-existing conditions. By that date, the island had performed 74 tests of which three were positive.<ref name=\"guardian-tobago-5april\">{{Cite web|url=https://guardian.co.tt/news/tobago-records-1st-covid19-death-6.2.1092936.a38ec6fa6d |title=Tobago records 1st COVID-19 death |date=5 April 2020 |website=Trinidad and Tobago Guardian}}</ref> Overall the country had submitted 797 tests to [[Caribbean_Public_Health_Agency|CARPHA]] for testing, of which 104 were positive, resulting in seven deaths and one recovery.<ref name=\"guardian-5april\">{{Cite web|url=https://guardian.co.tt/news/tt-has-104-confirmed-covid19-cases-deaths-now-at-7-6.2.1092952.6f0f0dc797 |title=T&T has 104 confirmed COVID-19 cases; deaths now at 7 |date=5 April 2020 |website=Trinidad and Tobago Guardian}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 April, a group of over 40 people stranded in [[Suriname]] are in a desperate situation. Despite multiple contacts to the Consulate and [[CARICOM]], no plans to repatriate them have been made. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.starnieuws.com/index.php/welcome/index/nieuwsitem/58140|title=More than 40 Trinidadian desperate in Suriname|website=Suriname Herald|language=nl|access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Prevention efforts ==\nHealth Minister [[Terrance Deyalsingh]], announced that [[Trinidad and Tobago]] had decided to implement restrictions on persons traveling from [[China]]. Persons who are living or who have visited China, will be barred from entering Trinidad and Tobago unless they had already been out of China 14 days prior to attempting to travel to Trinidad & Tobago.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.looptt.com/content/covid-19-tt-closes-borders-non-nationals-14-days |title = COVID-19: T&T closes borders to non-nationals for 14 days}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.caribbean360.com/news/trinidad-tobago-shuts-out-international-community-for-two-weeks-to-stem-spread-of-covid-19 |title = Trinidad & Tobago Shuts Out International Community to Stem Spread of COVID-19; Schools Closed|date = 16 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"TT Cabinet announces 14-day travel restrictions\">{{cite web |url=http://www.guardian.co.tt/neo/NeoProxy.dll?app=NeoDirect&com=6/2/1042978/7a4c342a7f |title=Cabinet announces 14-day travel restrictions from China |website=guardian.co.tt |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222113407/https://www.guardian.co.tt/neo/NeoProxy.dll?app=NeoDirect&com=6%2F2%2F1042978%2F7a4c342a7f |archive-date=22 February 2020 |access-date=27 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian_3_more\">{{cite web | url=http://www.guardian.co.tt/news/3-more-european-nations-on-tts-covidrestricted-list-6.2.1076451.75af2508a7 | title=3 more European nations on T&T's COVID-restricted list}}</ref> Travellers whose flights originate from&nbsp;Italy, South Korea, Singapore, Japan, Iran, Germany, Spain, and France are also to be restricted.<ref name=\"guardian_3_more\"/> On 16 March, [[Prime Minister of Trinidad and Tobago|Prime Minister]] [[Keith Rowley]] announced that the country will close its borders to everyone except Trinidad and Tobago nationals and health workers for the next 14 days. Additionally, bars were to be closed and the school closures extended until 20 April.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/latestnews/Trinidad_and_Tobago_bans_all_non_nationals_from_entering |title = Jamaica Observer Limited}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web | url=https://wired868.com/2020/03/16/trinidad-and-tobago-unplugged-rowley-closes-nations-borders-for-14-days-pubs-to-shut-down/ |title = Trinidad and Tobago unplugged: Rowley closes nation's borders for 14 days; pubs to shut down|date = 16 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Nanton|first=Sampson|url=http://www.guardian.co.tt/news/tt-shuts-down-borders-bars-to-be-closed-6.2.1080079.6b07bec899|title=T&T shuts down borders, bars to be closed|date=16 March 2020|work=Trinidad and Tobago Guardian|access-date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.guardian.co.tt/news/government-ramps-up-anticovid19-measures-in-tt-6.2.1080074.dcb235b8d3 |title = Government ramps up anti-COVID-19 measures in T&T}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.caribbean360.com/news/trinidad-tobago-shuts-out-international-community-for-two-weeks-to-stem-spread-of-covid-19 | title=Trinidad & Tobago Shuts Out International Community to Stem Spread of COVID-19; Schools Closed| date=16 March 2020}}</ref> The closure will come into effect by midnight on 17 March.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Clyne|first=Kalifa Sarah|url=https://newsday.co.tt/2020/03/16/government-shuts-tt-borders/|title=Government shuts TT borders|date=16 March 2020|work=Trinidad and Tobago Newsday|access-date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=CMC, Added 16 March 2020 |url=https://www.nationnews.com/nationnews/news/244418/trinidad-lockdown |title=Trinidad on lockdown - NationNews Barbados - Local, Regional and International News |publisher=Nationnews.com |date= |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.caribbeannationalweekly.com/news/caribbean-news/trinidad-and-tobago-bans-all-non-nationals-from-entering-country-for-14-days/ |title = Trinidad and Tobago Bans All Non-Nationals from Entering Country for 14 Days|date = 16 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web | url=https://globalvoices.org/2020/03/16/trinidad-tobago-closes-its-borders-as-covid-19-cases-double-to-four/ |title = Trinidad & Tobago closes its borders as COVID-19 cases double to four \u00b7 Global Voices|date = 16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 March, Rowley announced that schools and universities would be closed across the nation for one week due to the coronavirus fears.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.looptt.com/content/rowley-schools-universities-be-closed-one-week|title=Rowley: Schools, universities to be closed for one week|website=looptt.com|language=en|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://trinidadexpress.com/newsextra/schools-universities-close-for-one-week-to-slow-spread-of/article_fae5fb9a-655a-11ea-943a-ab529a1887a4.html|title=Schools, universities close for one week, to slow spread of COVID-19|website=Trinidad Express Newspapers|language=en|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> On 16 March, the closure was extended until 20 April.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.guardian.co.tt/news/schools-to-remain-closed-until-april-20-6.2.1080081.c799fe6774 | title=Schools to remain closed until April 20}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nOn 15 March, Police Commissioner of T&T [[Gary Griffith]] said he would be going into self-quarantine.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/coronavirus-trinidad-police-commissioner-gary-griffith-to-self-quarantine/ | title=Coronavirus: Trinidad Police Commissioner Gary Griffith to self-quarantine| date=16 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.stabroeknews.com/2020/03/15/news/regional/trinidad/trinidad-police-commissioner-gary-griffith-to-self-quarantine/ |title = Trinidad Police Commissioner Gary Griffith to self-quarantine|date = 15 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://newsday.co.tt/2020/03/15/commissioner-griffith-is-back-self-quarantines-for-14-days/ |title = Commissioner Griffith is back; self quarantines for 14 days|date = 15 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://newsday.co.tt/2020/03/14/griffith-on-return-from-london-i-will-go-in-self-quarantine/ | title=Griffith on return from London: I will go in self-quarantine| date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nMany [[Hindu]] associations cancelled [[Phagwa]], [[Navratri]], [[Ram Navami]], and [[Hanuman Jayanti]] celebrations.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://newsday.co.tt/2020/03/13/no-phagwa-in-south-trinidad/ |title = No Phagwa in south Trinidad|date = 14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.guardian.co.tt/news/coronavirus-scare-cancels-phagwa-celebrations-6.2.1078080.d304532f77 | title=Coronavirus scare cancels Phagwa celebrations}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://trinidadexpress.com/newsextra/phagwa-elr-concert-cancelled/article_cc496ad8-654b-11ea-8c8f-93496728f5aa.html |title = Phagwa, ELR concert cancelled}}</ref> Many other events were also cancelled or postponed.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://newsday.co.tt/2020/03/12/events-cancelled-over-covid19-fears/ | title=Events cancelled over covid19 fears| date=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://newsday.co.tt/2020/03/13/tt-regional-events-cancelled-over-covid19/ | title=TT, regional events cancelled over covid19| date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nRestrictions were put in place with regards to prisons nationwide.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://trinidadexpress.com/newsextra/prisons-lock-down-over-covid/article_8ec5c80a-679e-11ea-941d-cfd28e6c7b02.html |title = Prisons lock down over COVID-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.looptt.com/content/prison-service-limits-visits-prevent-covid-19-spread |title = Prison Service limits visits to prevent COVID-19 spread}}</ref> BPTT closed their offices in their response to the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/coronavirus-trinidad-and-tobago-natural-gas-company-bptt-closes-offices/ |title = Coronavirus: Trinidad and Tobago natural gas company BPTT closes offices|date = 16 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.guardian.co.tt/news/bptt-closes-offices-for-one-month-6.2.1079654.ef40f103f9 | title=BPTT closes offices for one month}}</ref> Deyalsingh said there were 3,000 test kits in Trinidad as of 16 March and 1000 more would be coming.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://newsday.co.tt/2020/03/16/3000-covid19-test-kits-in-tt/ |title = 3,000 covid19 test kits in TT|date = 16 March 2020}}</ref> Labour Minister [[Jennifer Baptiste-Primus]] announced that pandemic leave would be made available to workers with children.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.guardian.co.tt/news/pandemic-leave-for-workers-with-children-6.2.1079440.5954f6b6c8 |title = Pandemic leave for workers with children}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/trinidad-workers-you-can-get-pandemic-leave/ | title=Trinidad: Workers, you can get Pandemic Leave| date=16 March 2020}}</ref> On 21 March, National Security Minister [[Stuart Young (politician)|Stuart Young]] announced the closure of all borders to everyone (including nationals & non nationals) effective midnight on Sunday 22 March. He said no international flights would be allowed to enter the country.\nHowever, cargo vessels bringing food and pharmaceuticals into the country would be allowed entry.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://trinidadexpress.com/newsextra/t-t-s-borders-closed-to-all/article_5061e42c-6b8b-11ea-8328-3f8003c18b6f.html|title=T&T's borders closed to all}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April, Rowley extended the stay-at-home order to 30 April. He announced that until that date all restaurants would be closed, and several business such as supermarkets, bakeries, pharmacies and hardwares would have adjusted opening hours. He also said that people were to wear [[Cloth_facemask|facemasks]] when in public, and that the government would work on distributing masks.<ref name=\"guardian-stayhome-6april\">{{Cite web|url=https://guardian.co.tt/news/stayathome-order-extended-pm-says-all-restaurants-will-be-closed-6.2.1093520.0305392a80 |title=Stay-at-Home order extended, PM says all restaurants will be closed |date=6 April 2020 |website=Trinidad and Tobago Guardian}}</ref>\n\n== Criticisms of government accounts ==\nEven though the first case of COVID-19 was formally diagnosed on March 12th and attributed to a traveler from Switzerland, there have been suspicions about the virus circulating locally before then. A visitor to Trinidad and Tobago who returned to Alberta, Canada, was formally diagnosed with the virus there in early March.<ref name=\"alberta\">{{cite news |last1=Hudes |first1=Sammy |title='A new normal': Alberta confirms seven new COVID-19 cases, four from Calgary area |url=https://calgaryherald.com/news/local-news/province-announces-seven-new-coronavirus-cases-including-four-from-calgary-area/ |accessdate=17 April 2020 |publisher=Calgary Herald |date=11 March 2020}}</ref> The province's chief medical officer of health made the announcement on March 11th<ref name=\"alberta\" />, a day before the first case in Trinidad and Tobago.\n\nOn April 16th, [[Kamla Persad-Bissessar]], the former Prime Minister and current Opposition Leader, demanded that the government \"come clean\" about their testing capacity as well as the \"true state of the coronavirus spread in Trinidad and Tobago.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Kamla slams 'political freak show', demands 'true' COVID-19 stats |url=https://www.looptt.com/content/kamla-slams-political-freak-show-demands-true-covid-19-stats |accessdate=17 April 2020 |publisher=Loop News |date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Caribbean Public Health Agency]]\n\n== External links ==\n* Official site [http://www.health.gov.tt health.gov.tt]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Trinidad and Tobago]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Caribbean|Trinidad and Tobago]]\n[[Category:2020 in Trinidad and Tobago|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Trinidad and Tobago]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in the Republic of Trinidad and Tobago}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Trinidad and Tobago\n| first_case      = [[Trinidad and Tobago]]\n| total_ili       = \n| suspected_cases = \n| confirmed_cases = 115<ref name=\"trinidad-21april\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.health.gov.tt/sitepages/default.aspx?id=293 |title=Covid-19 (Novel Coronavirus) |access-date=21 April 2020 |website=health.gov.tt}}</ref> (2020-04-21)\n| recovery_cases  = 28<ref name=\"trinidad-20april\"/>\n| deaths          = 8<ref name=\"trinidad-20april\"/>\n| origin          = [[Wuhan, China]]\n| arrival_date    = 12 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=12|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| location        = [[Trinidad and Tobago]]\n| map1            = \n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| legend3         = \n| map3            = \n| legend2         = \n| map2            = \n| legend1         = \n| website         = [http://www.health.gov.tt health.gov.tt]\n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached the [[Republic of Trinidad and Tobago]] in March 2020.\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]],<ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |last= |first= |date= |website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/>\n\n== Timeline ==\n===March 2020===\nOn 12 March, the Republic of Trinidad and Tobago recorded its first case of COVID-19. It was a 52-year-old man who had recently been to [[Switzerland]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://dominicanewsonline.com/news/homepage/news/trinidad-tobago-confirms-first-case-of-coronavirus-covid-19/ |title = Trinidad & Tobago confirms first case of coronavirus (COVID - 19) |work=Dominica News Online |date = 13 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.looptt.com/content/moh-announces-tt-has-one-case-covid-19|title=MOH: One case of COVID-19 confirmed in T&T|website=looptt.com|language=en|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/latestnews/Trinidad_records_first_case_of_coronavirus|title=Jamaica Observer Limited|website=Jamaica Observer|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.guardian.co.tt/news/tt-gets-first-case-of-coronavirus-covid19-6.2.1077775.1564a3d6e9|title=T&T gets first case of coronavirus COVID-19|last=Nanton|first=Sampson|date=12 March 2020|website=Trinidad and Tobago Guardian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://trinidadexpress.com/newsextra/t-t-confirms-first-case-of-coronavirus/article_5c05b35a-6495-11ea-8bd4-1bba999d27a3.html|title=T&T confirms first case of coronavirus|website=Trinidad Express Newspapers|language=en|access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref> He was self-isolated before he began experiencing symptoms of COVID-19. Contact tracing for the passengers of the patient's flight is being conducted.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nOn 13 March, a second case of COVID-19 was recorded by Trinidad and Tobago.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://trinidadexpress.com/newsextra/t-t-records-nd-case-of-covid/article_dbd560e6-6592-11ea-adf9-9b60cb64b6db.html |title = T&T records 2nd case of COVID-19 |work=Daily Express |date=13 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://globalvoices.org/2020/03/14/trinidad-tobago-clamps-down-as-two-cases-of-covid-19-confirmed/ | title=Trinidad & Tobago clamps down as two cases of COVID-19 are confirmed |work= Global Voices| date=14 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.guardian.co.tt/news/second-covid19-case-confirmed-6.2.1078784.1b403b46dd |title = Second COVID-19 case confirmed }}</ref> The patient, a 66-year-old male with an unknown travel history, presented himself at a health facility and was soon isolated. Others who may have been exposed to the patient are also being quarantined.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.looptt.com/content/ministry-health-confirms-second-case-covid-19-tt|title=Ministry of Health confirms second case of COVID-19 in T&T|website=looptt.com|language=en|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.stabroeknews.com/2020/03/15/news/regional/trinidad/66-year-old-man-is-trinidad-tobagos-second-covid-19-case/ | title=66-year-old man is Trinidad & Tobago's second COVID-19 case |work=Starbroek News | date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.guardian.co.tt/news/tt-now-up-to-4-covid19-cases-6.2.1079739.e6882b3e89 |title = T&T now up to 4 COVID-19 cases |work=Trinidad & Tobago Guardian |access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://wired868.com/2020/03/13/sixty-six-year-old-man-confirmed-as-trinidads-second-covid-19-case/ | title=Sixty-six year old man confirmed as Trinidad's second Covid-19 case |work=Wired868.com | date=14 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nTwo more cases were confirmed on the night of 15 March, bringing the total to 4 cases.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.looptt.com/content/moh-confirms-two-more-covid-19-cases-tt | title=MOH confirms two more COVID-19 cases in T&T |work=looptt.com |date=15 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/trinidad-and-tobago-now-has-4-confirmed-coronavirus-disease-covid-19-patients/ |title = Trinidad and Tobago now has 4 confirmed coronavirus COVID-19 patients |work=St. Lucia News Online |date = 16 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://trinidadexpress.com/newsextra/t-t-now-has-confirmed-covid--victims/article_b3eb4662-6728-11ea-a920-0b96b8307903.html |title = T&T now has 4 confirmed COVID-19 victims}}</ref> A fifth case was confirmed on 16 March.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://trinidadexpress.com/newsextra/t-t-confirms-th-covid--victim/article_48e13c62-67e8-11ea-ba35-8b36de2e2dd9.html | title=T&T confirms 5th COVID-19 victim}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.stabroeknews.com/2020/03/17/news/regional/trinidad/trinidad-confirms-5th-coronavirus-case/ | title=Trinidad confirms 5th coronavirus case| date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.guardian.co.tt/news/5th-tt-covid19-case-confirmed-6.2.1080515.439cfd44ef |title = 5th T&T COVID-19 case confirmed}}</ref> On 17 March, another two cases were confirmed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://trinidadexpress.com/newsextra/t-t-now-has-confirmed-covid--cases/article_25ca5eb6-68c4-11ea-9d56-0f5f6a3983f8.html|title=T&T now has 7 confirmed COVID-19 cases|website=Trinidad Express Newspapers|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/trinidad-and-tobago-now-has-7-confirmed-coronavirus-covid-19-cases/|title=Trinidad and Tobago now has 7 confirmed coronavirus-COVID-19 cases|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref> Another two cases were confirmed on 19 March.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://trinidadexpress.com/news/t-t-now-has-cases-of-covid/article_2d9b004e-69c5-11ea-a498-5b9a526e67c6.html |title = T&T now has 9 cases of COVID-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.guardian.co.tt/news/tt-covid19-cases-now-up-to-9-6.2.1082264.95a5c787ac |title = T&T COVID-19 cases now up to 9}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.looptt.com/content/moh-reports-two-new-cases-covid-19 |title = MOH reports two new cases of COVID-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/trinidad-tobago-now-at-9-confirmed-covid-19-cases/ | title=Trinidad & Tobago now at 9 confirmed COVID-19 cases| date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, 40 more cases were confirmed. Sixty eight (68) nationals left for a 7-day cruise on the Caribbean sea on 5 March. After a suspected outbreak of COVID-19 on board, the Costa Favolosa was forced to anchor off the coast of Guadeloupe for several days. The nationals returned to Trinidad and Tobago on 17 March via a chartered flight from Guadeloupe. They were immediately screened and tested at Piarco International Airport and later taken to a quarantine facility. On 21 March it was confirmed that 40 of the 68 persons that were quarantined tested positive for COVID-19, bringing the total number of confirmed cases to 49.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guardian.co.tt/news/68-trinis-back-from-illfated-cruise-quarantined-in-balandra-6.2.1082228.4a205ffd90|title=68 Trinis back from ill-fated cruise quarantined in Balandra}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guardian.co.tt/news/40-new-covid19-cases-hospitalised-at-couva-6.2.1083879.9e92dd5f7d#.XnYtirdvus|title= 40 new COVID-19 cases hospitalised at Couva}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://trinidadexpress.com/news/local/anxiety-over-stranded-trinis/article_d2215fb8-68bd-11ea-8b3b-2b1f2d45ce34.html|title=Anxiety over stranded trinis}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, COVID-19 claimed its first victim in Trinidad.\nHe was a seventy-seven-year-old male with known pre-existing medical conditions.\n\nOn 26 March, the second reported COVID-19 death was an eighty-year-old male with pre-existing medical conditions. He was among the rescued cruise ship passengers quarantined at Camp Balandra.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://trinidadexpress.com/newsextra/t-t-records-nd-covid--death/article_19988bb0-7038-11ea-a9cf-6f836c8eabc2.html|title=T&T records 2nd COVID-19 death|website=Trinidad Express Newspapers|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> The Ministry of Health also reported that one of the patients who tested positive, was quarantined and treated has since been discharged.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsday.co.tt/2020/03/27/2nd-local-covid19-death-confirmed/|title=2nd local covid19 death confirmed|date=2020-03-27|website=Trinidad and Tobago Newsday|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\n=== April 2020 ===\nOn 5 April, Tobago recorded its first death, an elderly male with pre-existing conditions. By that date, the island had performed 74 tests of which three were positive.<ref name=\"guardian-tobago-5april\">{{Cite web|url=https://guardian.co.tt/news/tobago-records-1st-covid19-death-6.2.1092936.a38ec6fa6d |title=Tobago records 1st COVID-19 death |date=5 April 2020 |website=Trinidad and Tobago Guardian}}</ref> Overall the country had submitted 797 tests to [[Caribbean_Public_Health_Agency|CARPHA]] for testing, of which 104 were positive, resulting in seven deaths and one recovery.<ref name=\"guardian-5april\">{{Cite web|url=https://guardian.co.tt/news/tt-has-104-confirmed-covid19-cases-deaths-now-at-7-6.2.1092952.6f0f0dc797 |title=T&T has 104 confirmed COVID-19 cases; deaths now at 7 |date=5 April 2020 |website=Trinidad and Tobago Guardian}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 April, a group of over 40 people stranded in [[Suriname]] are in a desperate situation. Despite multiple contacts to the Consulate and [[CARICOM]], no plans to repatriate them have been made. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.starnieuws.com/index.php/welcome/index/nieuwsitem/58140|title=More than 40 Trinidadian desperate in Suriname|website=Suriname Herald|language=nl|access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Prevention efforts ==\nHealth Minister [[Terrance Deyalsingh]], announced that [[Trinidad and Tobago]] had decided to implement restrictions on persons traveling from [[China]]. Persons who are living or who have visited China, will be barred from entering Trinidad and Tobago unless they had already been out of China 14 days prior to attempting to travel to Trinidad & Tobago.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.looptt.com/content/covid-19-tt-closes-borders-non-nationals-14-days |title = COVID-19: T&T closes borders to non-nationals for 14 days}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.caribbean360.com/news/trinidad-tobago-shuts-out-international-community-for-two-weeks-to-stem-spread-of-covid-19 |title = Trinidad & Tobago Shuts Out International Community to Stem Spread of COVID-19; Schools Closed|date = 16 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"TT Cabinet announces 14-day travel restrictions\">{{cite web |url=http://www.guardian.co.tt/neo/NeoProxy.dll?app=NeoDirect&com=6/2/1042978/7a4c342a7f |title=Cabinet announces 14-day travel restrictions from China |website=guardian.co.tt |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222113407/https://www.guardian.co.tt/neo/NeoProxy.dll?app=NeoDirect&com=6%2F2%2F1042978%2F7a4c342a7f |archive-date=22 February 2020 |access-date=27 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian_3_more\">{{cite web | url=http://www.guardian.co.tt/news/3-more-european-nations-on-tts-covidrestricted-list-6.2.1076451.75af2508a7 | title=3 more European nations on T&T's COVID-restricted list}}</ref> Travellers whose flights originate from&nbsp;Italy, South Korea, Singapore, Japan, Iran, Germany, Spain, and France are also to be restricted.<ref name=\"guardian_3_more\"/> On 16 March, [[Prime Minister of Trinidad and Tobago|Prime Minister]] [[Keith Rowley]] announced that the country will close its borders to everyone except Trinidad and Tobago nationals and health workers for the next 14 days. Additionally, bars were to be closed and the school closures extended until 20 April.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/latestnews/Trinidad_and_Tobago_bans_all_non_nationals_from_entering |title = Jamaica Observer Limited}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web | url=https://wired868.com/2020/03/16/trinidad-and-tobago-unplugged-rowley-closes-nations-borders-for-14-days-pubs-to-shut-down/ |title = Trinidad and Tobago unplugged: Rowley closes nation's borders for 14 days; pubs to shut down|date = 16 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Nanton|first=Sampson|url=http://www.guardian.co.tt/news/tt-shuts-down-borders-bars-to-be-closed-6.2.1080079.6b07bec899|title=T&T shuts down borders, bars to be closed|date=16 March 2020|work=Trinidad and Tobago Guardian|access-date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.guardian.co.tt/news/government-ramps-up-anticovid19-measures-in-tt-6.2.1080074.dcb235b8d3 |title = Government ramps up anti-COVID-19 measures in T&T}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.caribbean360.com/news/trinidad-tobago-shuts-out-international-community-for-two-weeks-to-stem-spread-of-covid-19 | title=Trinidad & Tobago Shuts Out International Community to Stem Spread of COVID-19; Schools Closed| date=16 March 2020}}</ref> The closure will come into effect by midnight on 17 March.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Clyne|first=Kalifa Sarah|url=https://newsday.co.tt/2020/03/16/government-shuts-tt-borders/|title=Government shuts TT borders|date=16 March 2020|work=Trinidad and Tobago Newsday|access-date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=CMC, Added 16 March 2020 |url=https://www.nationnews.com/nationnews/news/244418/trinidad-lockdown |title=Trinidad on lockdown - NationNews Barbados - Local, Regional and International News |publisher=Nationnews.com |date= |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.caribbeannationalweekly.com/news/caribbean-news/trinidad-and-tobago-bans-all-non-nationals-from-entering-country-for-14-days/ |title = Trinidad and Tobago Bans All Non-Nationals from Entering Country for 14 Days|date = 16 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web | url=https://globalvoices.org/2020/03/16/trinidad-tobago-closes-its-borders-as-covid-19-cases-double-to-four/ |title = Trinidad & Tobago closes its borders as COVID-19 cases double to four \u00b7 Global Voices|date = 16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 March, Rowley announced that schools and universities would be closed across the nation for one week due to the coronavirus fears.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.looptt.com/content/rowley-schools-universities-be-closed-one-week|title=Rowley: Schools, universities to be closed for one week|website=looptt.com|language=en|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://trinidadexpress.com/newsextra/schools-universities-close-for-one-week-to-slow-spread-of/article_fae5fb9a-655a-11ea-943a-ab529a1887a4.html|title=Schools, universities close for one week, to slow spread of COVID-19|website=Trinidad Express Newspapers|language=en|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> On 16 March, the closure was extended until 20 April.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.guardian.co.tt/news/schools-to-remain-closed-until-april-20-6.2.1080081.c799fe6774 | title=Schools to remain closed until April 20}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nOn 15 March, Police Commissioner of T&T [[Gary Griffith]] said he would be going into self-quarantine.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/coronavirus-trinidad-police-commissioner-gary-griffith-to-self-quarantine/ | title=Coronavirus: Trinidad Police Commissioner Gary Griffith to self-quarantine| date=16 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.stabroeknews.com/2020/03/15/news/regional/trinidad/trinidad-police-commissioner-gary-griffith-to-self-quarantine/ |title = Trinidad Police Commissioner Gary Griffith to self-quarantine|date = 15 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://newsday.co.tt/2020/03/15/commissioner-griffith-is-back-self-quarantines-for-14-days/ |title = Commissioner Griffith is back; self quarantines for 14 days|date = 15 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://newsday.co.tt/2020/03/14/griffith-on-return-from-london-i-will-go-in-self-quarantine/ | title=Griffith on return from London: I will go in self-quarantine| date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nMany [[Hindu]] associations cancelled [[Phagwa]], [[Navratri]], [[Ram Navami]], and [[Hanuman Jayanti]] celebrations.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://newsday.co.tt/2020/03/13/no-phagwa-in-south-trinidad/ |title = No Phagwa in south Trinidad|date = 14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.guardian.co.tt/news/coronavirus-scare-cancels-phagwa-celebrations-6.2.1078080.d304532f77 | title=Coronavirus scare cancels Phagwa celebrations}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://trinidadexpress.com/newsextra/phagwa-elr-concert-cancelled/article_cc496ad8-654b-11ea-8c8f-93496728f5aa.html |title = Phagwa, ELR concert cancelled}}</ref> Many other events were also cancelled or postponed.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://newsday.co.tt/2020/03/12/events-cancelled-over-covid19-fears/ | title=Events cancelled over covid19 fears| date=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://newsday.co.tt/2020/03/13/tt-regional-events-cancelled-over-covid19/ | title=TT, regional events cancelled over covid19| date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nRestrictions were put in place with regards to prisons nationwide.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://trinidadexpress.com/newsextra/prisons-lock-down-over-covid/article_8ec5c80a-679e-11ea-941d-cfd28e6c7b02.html |title = Prisons lock down over COVID-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.looptt.com/content/prison-service-limits-visits-prevent-covid-19-spread |title = Prison Service limits visits to prevent COVID-19 spread}}</ref> BPTT closed their offices in their response to the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/coronavirus-trinidad-and-tobago-natural-gas-company-bptt-closes-offices/ |title = Coronavirus: Trinidad and Tobago natural gas company BPTT closes offices|date = 16 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.guardian.co.tt/news/bptt-closes-offices-for-one-month-6.2.1079654.ef40f103f9 | title=BPTT closes offices for one month}}</ref> Deyalsingh said there were 3,000 test kits in Trinidad as of 16 March and 1000 more would be coming.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://newsday.co.tt/2020/03/16/3000-covid19-test-kits-in-tt/ |title = 3,000 covid19 test kits in TT|date = 16 March 2020}}</ref> Labour Minister [[Jennifer Baptiste-Primus]] announced that pandemic leave would be made available to workers with children.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.guardian.co.tt/news/pandemic-leave-for-workers-with-children-6.2.1079440.5954f6b6c8 |title = Pandemic leave for workers with children}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/trinidad-workers-you-can-get-pandemic-leave/ | title=Trinidad: Workers, you can get Pandemic Leave| date=16 March 2020}}</ref> On 21 March, National Security Minister [[Stuart Young (politician)|Stuart Young]] announced the closure of all borders to everyone (including nationals & non nationals) effective midnight on Sunday 22 March. He said no international flights would be allowed to enter the country.\nHowever, cargo vessels bringing food and pharmaceuticals into the country would be allowed entry.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://trinidadexpress.com/newsextra/t-t-s-borders-closed-to-all/article_5061e42c-6b8b-11ea-8328-3f8003c18b6f.html|title=T&T's borders closed to all}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April, Rowley extended the stay-at-home order to 30 April. He announced that until that date all restaurants would be closed, and several business such as supermarkets, bakeries, pharmacies and hardwares would have adjusted opening hours. He also said that people were to wear [[Cloth_facemask|facemasks]] when in public, and that the government would work on distributing masks.<ref name=\"guardian-stayhome-6april\">{{Cite web|url=https://guardian.co.tt/news/stayathome-order-extended-pm-says-all-restaurants-will-be-closed-6.2.1093520.0305392a80 |title=Stay-at-Home order extended, PM says all restaurants will be closed |date=6 April 2020 |website=Trinidad and Tobago Guardian}}</ref>\n\n== Criticisms of government accounts ==\nEven though the first case of COVID-19 was formally diagnosed on March 12th and attributed to a traveler from Switzerland, there have been suspicions about the virus circulating locally before then. A visitor to Trinidad and Tobago who returned to Alberta, Canada, was formally diagnosed with the virus there in early March.<ref name=\"alberta\">{{cite news |last1=Hudes |first1=Sammy |title='A new normal': Alberta confirms seven new COVID-19 cases, four from Calgary area |url=https://calgaryherald.com/news/local-news/province-announces-seven-new-coronavirus-cases-including-four-from-calgary-area/ |accessdate=17 April 2020 |publisher=Calgary Herald |date=11 March 2020}}</ref> The province's chief medical officer of health made the announcement on March 11th<ref name=\"alberta\" />, a day before the first case in Trinidad and Tobago.\n\nOn April 16th, [[Kamla Persad-Bissessar]], the former Prime Minister and current Opposition Leader, demanded that the government \"come clean\" about their testing capacity as well as the \"true state of the coronavirus spread in Trinidad and Tobago.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Kamla slams 'political freak show', demands 'true' COVID-19 stats |url=https://www.looptt.com/content/kamla-slams-political-freak-show-demands-true-covid-19-stats |accessdate=17 April 2020 |publisher=Loop News |date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Caribbean Public Health Agency]]\n\n== External links ==\n* Official site [http://www.health.gov.tt health.gov.tt]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Trinidad and Tobago]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Caribbean|Trinidad and Tobago]]\n[[Category:2020 in Trinidad and Tobago|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Trinidad and Tobago]]\n", "name_user": "KittenKlub", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Trinidad_and_Tobago"}
{"title_page": "Tuluva Vellala", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{refimprove|date=February 2012}}\n{{Unreferenced|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{use Indian English|date=September 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n| image            = \n| caption          = From Left top: Vallal Pachayappa Mudaliar, Dr. [[C. Natesa Mudaliar]], Namakkal Kavignar [[Venkatarama Ramalingam Pillai | V Ramalingam Pillai ]], [[Maniammai | E V R Maniyammai]].\n| group            = Tuluva Vellala\n| popplace         = [[Tamil Nadu]], [[Andhra Pradesh]], [[Karnataka]]\nCities : [[Chennai]], [[Bangalore]], [[Vellore]]\n| languages        = Previously [[Tulu language|Tulu]], now [[Tamil language|Tamil]]\n| religions        = Predominantly [[Shaivism]], also [[Vaishnavism]], [[Christianity]]\n| related          = [[Vellalar]], [[Tamil people]]\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n}}\n'''Tuluva Vellala''' (Alternate spelling: ''Thuluva vellala/Tozhu vellala'') is the Vellalar community found in northern Tamil Nadu, southern Andhra Pradesh and southern Karnataka.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}They are also migrated to several cantonment towns in North India, Bhurma and Malaya in British times.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} \n\nBeing the Socio-economically forward non-brahmin caste, Tuluva Vellala played a significant role in Non-Brahmin movement in Madras presidency.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} \n\nTuluva Vellalars found themselves superior to Brahmins, well educated and Anglophilic. They are highly majority in Ranipet and [[Tiruvannamalai]] districts. Tuluva Vellalars are said to be migrated from Mangalore (Tulu region) to Arcot during [[Krishnadevaraya]] period or before, hence named as Tuluva Vellala.{{cn|date=April 2020}}Mudaliar, Pillai, Odeyar are the most common titles used.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} \n\n==Notable Tuluva Vellalar==\n\n* Shaktivel Kadirvel\n* [[C. Natesa Mudaliar]]<ref>Caste, Nationalism and Ethnicity- Author Jacob Pandian Page No 116</ref>, one of the founders of Justice Party\n* Vallal [[Pachaiyappa Mudaliar]] - Philanthropist, Industrialist, Founder of Pachiappa college, Chennai.\n*[[Kanakaraya Mudali]], Chief [[dubash]] for the [[French East India Company]]\n* Rao bahadur Sir Dr. [[C. Natesa Mudaliar]] - Founder of  Justice party, later Renamed as Dravidar kazhagam\n*Diwan Bahadur [[C. S. Ratnasabhapathy Mudaliar|Coimbatore S. Ratnasabhapathi Mudaliar]], OBE - Prominent leader of Justice party, Industrialist and Philanthropist, Father of Modern Coimbatore. Locality of [[R. S. Puram, Coimbatore|R. S. Puram]] (Ratnasabhapathipuram) is named after him. Major financial contributor of Bhavani Sagar dam.\n*Diwan bahadur Sir [[Arcot Ramasamy Mudaliar|Arcot Ramaswamy Mudaliar, KSCI]] - Diwan of Mysore, Philanthropist, Prominent Non-Brahmin movement leader\n*Sir [[A. Lakshmanaswami Mudaliar|Arcot Lakshamanasami Mudaliar]], KCSI - Scholar, Doctor, Author of Indian Obstetrics book.\n*Rao bahadur Vellore [[Krishnaswami|Krishnasamy mudaliar]] \n*[[V. L. Ethiraj|V.L.Ethiraj Mudaliar]], founder of Ethiraj College for Women, Chennai; first Indian to be appointed as Crown Prosecutor by the British Raj.\n*[[A. Ranganatha Mudaliar|Arcot Ranganatha Mudaliar]] - Indian politician and theosophist from [[Bellary]]. served as the Minister of Public Health and Excise for the [[Madras Presidency]] from 1926 to 1928.\n*Dharmarathnakara Rai Bahadur [[Arcot Narrainswamy Mudaliar|Arcot Narrainsawmy Mudaliar]] '''-''' founded the R.B.A.N.M.'s Educational Charities and R.B.A.N.M.'s Chattram.\n*[[Pammal Sambandha Mudaliar]]\n*[[Maniammai|E. V. R. Maniammai]] - First woman leader of any atheist movement in the world, Leader of [[Dravidar Kazhagam]], Life partner of Thanthai [[Periyar E. V. Ramasamy|Periyar]].\n* [[N. V. Natarajan]] - Co-founder of Dravida Munnetra kazhagam, former labour Minister. \n* [[P. U. Shanmugam]] - Prominent Dravidian politician, Former minister of PWD, former MLA - Tiruvannamalai.\n*[[A. C. Shanmugam|A C Shanmugam]] - Founder of New Justice Party, Former MP - Tirupattur, Chairman - Dr MGR University, Maduravoyal \n*[[G. Viswanathan|G Vishwanathan]] - Former MP, Vellore. Founder - Vellore Institute of Technology. \n*[[J. Anbazhagan]] - Former labor minister of DMK\n* [[Aircel|C Sivasankaran]] - Founder of Aircel communications, Sterling groups.\n*[[S. S. Krishnamoorthy|Agri S S Krishnamurthy]] - Former minister of Food, School education and Revenue of ADMK. \n* [[R. S. Bharathi]] - MP, Rajya sabha\n* [[Isari Velan]] - Yesteryears actor\n* [[Ishari K. Ganesh]]- Founder, Vel\u2019s university and Tamil movie producer\n\n==See also==\n* [[Tuluva Narasa Nayaka]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Vellalar]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Tamil Nadu]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{refimprove|date=February 2012}}\n{{Unreferenced|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{use Indian English|date=September 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n| image            = \n| caption          = From Left top: Vallal Pachayappa Mudaliar, Dr. [[C. Natesa Mudaliar]], Namakkal Kavignar [[Venkatarama Ramalingam Pillai | V Ramalingam Pillai ]], [[Maniammai | E V R Maniyammai]].\n| group            = Tuluva Vellala\n| popplace         = [[Tamil Nadu]], [[Andhra Pradesh]], [[Karnataka]]\nCities : [[Chennai]], [[Bangalore]], [[Vellore]]\n| languages        = Previously [[Tulu language|Tulu]], now [[Tamil language|Tamil]]\n| religions        = Predominantly [[Shaivism]], also [[Vaishnavism]], [[Christianity]]\n| related          = [[Vellalar]], [[Tamil people]]\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n}}\n'''Tuluva Vellala''' (Alternate spelling: ''Thuluva vellala/Tozhu vellala'') is the Vellalar community found in northern Tamil Nadu, southern Andhra Pradesh and southern Karnataka.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}They are also migrated to several cantonment towns in North India, Bhurma and Malaya in British times.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} \n\nBeing the Socio-economically forward non-brahmin caste, Tuluva Vellala played a significant role in Non-Brahmin movement in Madras presidency.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} \n\nTuluva Vellalars found themselves superior to Brahmins, well educated and Anglophilic. They are highly majority in Ranipet and [[Tiruvannamalai]] districts. Tuluva Vellalars are said to be migrated from Mangalore (Tulu region) to Arcot during [[Krishnadevaraya]] period or before, hence named as Tuluva Vellala.{{cn|date=April 2020}}Mudaliar, Pillai, Odeyar are the most common titles used.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} \n\n==Notable Tuluva Vellalar==\n* [[C. Natesa Mudaliar]]<ref>Caste, Nationalism and Ethnicity- Author Jacob Pandian Page No 116</ref>, one of the founders of Justice Party\n* Vallal [[Pachaiyappa Mudaliar]] - Philanthropist, Industrialist, Founder of Pachiappa college, Chennai.\n*[[Kanakaraya Mudali]], Chief [[dubash]] for the [[French East India Company]]\n* Rao bahadur Sir Dr. [[C. Natesa Mudaliar]] - Founder of  Justice party, later Renamed as Dravidar kazhagam\n*Diwan Bahadur [[C. S. Ratnasabhapathy Mudaliar|Coimbatore S. Ratnasabhapathi Mudaliar]], OBE - Prominent leader of Justice party, Industrialist and Philanthropist, Father of Modern Coimbatore. Locality of [[R. S. Puram, Coimbatore|R. S. Puram]] (Ratnasabhapathipuram) is named after him. Major financial contributor of Bhavani Sagar dam.\n*Diwan bahadur Sir [[Arcot Ramasamy Mudaliar|Arcot Ramaswamy Mudaliar, KSCI]] - Diwan of Mysore, Philanthropist, Prominent Non-Brahmin movement leader\n*Sir [[A. Lakshmanaswami Mudaliar|Arcot Lakshamanasami Mudaliar]], KCSI - Scholar, Doctor, Author of Indian Obstetrics book.\n*Rao bahadur Vellore [[Krishnaswami|Krishnasamy mudaliar]] \n*[[V. L. Ethiraj|V.L.Ethiraj Mudaliar]], founder of Ethiraj College for Women, Chennai; first Indian to be appointed as Crown Prosecutor by the British Raj.\n*[[A. Ranganatha Mudaliar|Arcot Ranganatha Mudaliar]] - Indian politician and theosophist from [[Bellary]]. served as the Minister of Public Health and Excise for the [[Madras Presidency]] from 1926 to 1928.\n*Dharmarathnakara Rai Bahadur [[Arcot Narrainswamy Mudaliar|Arcot Narrainsawmy Mudaliar]] '''-''' founded the R.B.A.N.M.'s Educational Charities and R.B.A.N.M.'s Chattram.\n*[[Pammal Sambandha Mudaliar]]\n*[[Maniammai|E. V. R. Maniammai]] - First woman leader of any atheist movement in the world, Leader of [[Dravidar Kazhagam]], Life partner of Thanthai [[Periyar E. V. Ramasamy|Periyar]].\n* [[N. V. Natarajan]] - Co-founder of Dravida Munnetra kazhagam, former labour Minister. \n* [[P. U. Shanmugam]] - Prominent Dravidian politician, Former minister of PWD, former MLA - Tiruvannamalai.\n*[[A. C. Shanmugam|A C Shanmugam]] - Founder of New Justice Party, Former MP - Tirupattur, Chairman - Dr MGR University, Maduravoyal \n*[[G. Viswanathan|G Vishwanathan]] - Former MP, Vellore. Founder - Vellore Institute of Technology. \n*[[J. Anbazhagan]] - Former labor minister of DMK\n* [[Aircel|C Sivasankaran]] - Founder of Aircel communications, Sterling groups.\n*[[S. S. Krishnamoorthy|Agri S S Krishnamurthy]] - Former minister of Food, School education and Revenue of ADMK. \n* [[R. S. Bharathi]] - MP, Rajya sabha\n* [[Isari Velan]] - Yesteryears actor\n* [[Ishari K. Ganesh]]- Founder, Vel\u2019s university and Tamil movie producer\n\n==See also==\n* [[Tuluva Narasa Nayaka]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Vellalar]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Tamil Nadu]]\n", "name_user": "122.181.205.141", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eNotable Tuluva Vellalar)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tuluva_Vellala"}
{"title_page": "Fernando del Valle", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n|name            = Fernando del Valle \n|image           = TENOR_FERNANDO_DEL_VALLE_ONSTAGE.jpg\n|image_size      = 220\n|caption         = del Valle in 2010\n|background      = solo_singer\n|birth_name      = Brian Stephen Skinner\n|alias           = \n|birth_date      = {{birth date|1964|02|28}}\n|birth_place     = [[New Orleans|New Orleans, Louisiana]], United States\n|death_date      = \n|death_place     = \n|instrument      = [[Tenor]]\n|genre           = [[Opera]]\n|occupation      = Opera singer\n|years_active    = \n|label           = \n}}\n\n'''Fernando del Valle''' (n\u00e9 Brian Stephen Skinner; February 28, 1964) is an American [[opera]]tic [[tenor]]. He is the son of Edward King Skinner II, a [[Korean War]] veteran<ref name=\"tributes.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tributes.com/show/Edward-King-Skinner-86579321|title=Edward Skinner Obituary - Metairie, Louisiana - Lake Lawn Metairie Funeral Home and Cemeteries|website=www.tributes.com}}</ref> and Concha Marina Mel\u00e9ndez del Valle. The grandson of Aranka Bischitz great great granddaughter of Baroness [[Johanna Bischitz von Heves]] and cousin  of [[Hungary|Hungarian]] [[radiochemist]] and [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry]] laureate [[George de Hevesy]] and Fernando Melendez del Valle-Parker. He is the nephew of the Architect [[:de:Manuel Roberto Mel\u00e9ndez Bischitz|Manuel Roberto Mel\u00e9ndez Bischitz]].\n\n==Ancestry==\nHe took the name del Valle in honour of his grandfather, Fernando Mel\u00e9ndez del Valle,<ref>[http://www.elsalvador.com/mwedh/nota/nota_completa.asp?idCat=6461&idArt=5301703] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141208000341/http://www.elsalvador.com/mwedh/nota/nota_completa.asp?idCat=6461&idArt=5301703 |date=2014-12-08 }}</ref> who was also a tenor and diplomat for [[El Salvador]] at the consulate of El Salvador in New Orleans.<ref>\"Santa Tecla, Cronolog\u00eda\" {{ISBN|99923-0-141-4}} Recopilada por Dr. Juan Jos\u00e9 Contreras Callejas, Mauricio Alvarado Cea Campo, \u00c1ngela Margarita Alvarado: Consejo National para la Cultura y el Arte, CONCULTURA, San Salvador 2004: Page 14, \"El Diario de Hoy\", November 30, 1985.</ref><ref>''New Orleans Magazine'', July 1999.</ref>\n\nHe is the great-great-grandson of [[Andr\u00e9s del Valle]], President of El Salvador in 1876<ref>Cuisine, Texas: a multiethnic feast, page 258, Joanne Smith, [[University of Texas Press]] (September 1, 2010), {{ISBN|978-0292728516}}</ref> and a direct descendant of Colonel [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda San Mart\u00edn]], [[President of El Salvador]] (1854\u201356) and founder of [[Santa Tecla, El Salvador]].<ref>[http://archive.laprensa.com.sv/20040822/opinion/opinion1.asp \"La distinguida genealog\u00eda de los San Mart\u00edn\"], ''Prensa Grafica'', August 22, 2004.</ref><ref>Morena Azucena, [http://www.elsalvador.com \"Un tenor l\u00edrico con ra\u00edces tecle\u00f1as\"], elsalvador.com, September 22, 2004, pg. 106</ref><ref>Gobernantes de El Salvador, Maria y Freddy Leistenschneider, 1980, pg. 137 (A. del Valle) & pg. 97 (J.M. San Martin) Publicaciones Del MinisterIo Del Interior, Imprenta Nacional, San Salvador, El Salvador.</ref>\n\nHe is the grandson of the Honorable Judge Robert J. Skinner,<ref>Gary Krist, ''Empire of Sin'', New York Times Sunday Book Review, November 6, 2014.</ref><ref name=\"tributes.com\"/> former recorder and treasurer (for the City of New Orleans), a regimental sergeant-major in [[World War One]], and the great grandson of Judge Edward King Skinner, who served on the city, criminal and civil district court benches, successively, over a total period of 52 years<ref>John C. Kelly, \"R.J. Skinner Taken by Death\", ''The New Orleans Item'', July 18, 1949.</ref><ref>Library Archives Analyst II, ''The Times-Picayune''.</ref><ref>Thomas K. Griffin, \"Skinner's Ward is on the Way\", ''The Times-Picayune'' Library Archives.</ref>\n\nIn 1880, he was appointed to first district court after the [[American Civil War|Civil War]]. A year after his retirement attorneys gave civil district court a portrait in oils of Judge Skinner.<ref>'E.K. Skinner retired Judge of Civil Court Dies\" The Times Picayune/New Orleans States Volume C---NO. 134, New Orleans, Sunday, June 7, 1936, pg. 6</ref>\n\nThe portrait by John Paul Parker, was presented to the court by United States Attorney Rene A. Viosca, who was then president of the New Orleans Bar Association.<ref>'E.K. Skinner retired Judge of Civil Court Dies\" The Times Picayune/New Orleans States Volume C---NO. 134, New Orleans, Sunday, June 7, 1936, Pages 1 and 6</ref><ref>\"Biographical and  Historical Memoirs of Louisiana\", Volume 2, pp. 388-89, Goodspeed Publishing Company, Chicago, 1892.</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nHe was born in [[New Orleans]].<ref>Richard Siklos, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk \"New Orleans: \"Big year for the Big Easy\"], January 17, 2003.</ref> A graduate of [[Brother Martin High School]], he received his Bachelor of Fine Arts from [[Tulane University]] as the recipient of the Treville Scholarship in Voice, and the Artists Diploma from [[Southern Methodist University]] as the Haggar Scholar.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\nAs a winner of the Dallas Opera Guild Vocal Competition he was awarded a Career Grant from The [[Dallas Opera]], the winner of the Stewart Award, the [[Austin Lyric Opera]] Vocal Competition, the [[Fort Worth Opera]] Competition and the Vocal Competition of the [[San Antonio Opera]] judged by [[Evelyn Lear]] and [[Richard Gaddes]].{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\nHe is an alumnus of the [[San Francisco Opera]]'s [[Merola Opera Program]] where he studied under the direction of [[Patrick Summers]] in 1992 and 1993. He later won the \"Bel Canto\" competition of Chicago and subsequently relocated to Italy where he studied under [[Carlo Bergonzi]] and, later, [[Thomas Hayward (tenor)|Thomas Hayward]] and [[Nicolai Gedda]].{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\n===Early years===\nDel Valle made his operatic debut at the age of seventeen (1981), as the First Shepherd in [[John Blow]]'s ''[[Venus and Adonis (Blow)]]'', at [[Loyola University New Orleans|Loyola University]] followed by roles in [[La rondine]], conducted by [[Maurice Peress]], ''[[Brigadoon]]'', ''[[Shenandoah (musical)|Shenandoah]]'' and ''[[The Merry Widow]]''.\n\nThe next year, after the intervention and advice of his [[Tulane]] professor, [[Deborah Drattell]], he became tenor soloist in Bach's \"St Matthew Passion\" with the New Orleans Philharmonic-Symphony Orchestra, [[Andrew Massey (conductor)|Andrew Massey]], conducting.  In 1986, he made his Boston debut in that composer's ''Christmas Oratorio'' in [[Jordan Hall]] as the winner of the Boston Premiere Ensembles Young Artist Competition. The following spring, his New York debut took place at [[Alice Tully Hall]], [[Lincoln Center]], with the Beethoven Society of New York.\n\nHe continued his career as a concert tenor with a repertoire that included Beethoven's ''[[Missa Solemnis (Beethoven)|Missa Solemnis]]'', and the Requiems of Verdi, [[Britten]] and [[Lloyd Webber]]. The tenor's [[Carnegie Hall]] debut occurred in 1993, with Mozart's \"Great\" Mass in C minor with the [[American Symphony Orchestra]].  He performed the tenor solos in [[George Frideric Handel]]'s ''Messiah'' for the [[Dallas Symphony Orchestra]], at the [[Morton H. Meyerson Symphony Center]] in 1994.  He made his European debut in 1995, singing in Beethoven's [[Symphony No. 9 (Beethoven)|Symphony No. 9]] with the [[Orchestra Sinfonica di Milano Giuseppe Verdi]].\n\nDel Valle's European operatic debut took place with the role of \"Don Jos\u00e9\" in the Hugo de Ana production of ''[[Carmen]]'' at the Teatro Comunale di [[Treviso]] under the vocal direction of [[Regina Resnik]] and conducted by [[Peter Maag]]. In 1996, he appeared as Rodolfo in ''[[La boh\u00e8me]]'', at the [[Teatro dell'Opera di Roma]], [[Vladimir Jurowski]], conducting.\n\n===1997\u2013present===\nIn 1997, del Valle appeared as 'don Jos\u00e9' at the Gran [[Teatro La Fenice]] in Venice, [[Isaac Karabtchevsky]], conducting 'Pinkerton' in ''Madama Butterfly'' with the [[Palm Beach Opera]], [[Anton Guadagno]], conducting and 'Faust' in [[Colmar]], France. He made his German debut in 1998 as 'Rodolfo' with the [[Frankfurt Opera]], under the direction of the venerated [[pedagogue]]/conductor, [[Klauspeter Seibel]], immediately following he appeared to critical acclaim,<ref>[[Andrew Porter (music critic)|Andrew Porter]], ''[[Financial Times]]'', October 26, 1998.<br>\"This ''Fosca'' was Wexford at its best. It brought forward a tenor of uncommon merit: del Valle was as firm as Domingo in his pure, true utterance but also able and eager, Bergonzi-wise, to \"melt\" from note to note in shapely phrases. (Caruso's splendour ''plus'' Gigli's charm make a good model)\"</ref><ref>[[Rodney Milnes]], ''[[The Times]]'', October 28, 1998.<br>\"....an exciting tenor, especially at the top of the register, who can shape a phrase with real sensitivity.\"</ref> at the [[Wexford Festival]] in Ireland as 'Paolo' in [[Fosca (opera)]] by [[Ant\u00f4nio Carlos Gomes]]. A series of important engagements followed, and since 1999, del Valle has appeared around the world, including performances in Frankfurt [[Alte Oper]], [[Strasbourg]] (Beethoven 9th Symphony, op. 125, with [[John Storgards]] conducting), Maastricht, [[Deutsche Oper am Rhein]], [[Theater Augsburg]], [[Tonhalle D\u00fcsseldorf]], [[Deutsche Oper Berlin]], [[Theater Dortmund]], [[Teatro Carlo Felice]], Bremen, Bergen, Costa Rica, Munich [[Gasteig]], [[Finnish National Opera]], Helsinki, [[Belo Horizonte]] in Brazil, the [[HIFA]] Festival in [[Harare|Harare, Zimbabwe]],<ref>Maxwell Sibanda, \"Zimbabwe: International Acts Set to Flavour Hifa\", ''The Harare Daily News'', April 29, 2003.</ref> [[Malm\u00f6, Sweden]], [[New Symphony Orchestra|New Symphony Orchestra of Sofia, Bulgaria]], [[Teatro Petruzzelli]] di [[Bari]], [[Torino]], [[Baveno]], Inaugural concert of the [[Umberto Giordano]] Festival with the [[RAI National Symphony Orchestra]], [[National Theatre Mannheim]], [[Badisches Staatstheater Karlsruhe]], [[Staatstheater Kassel]], Hamburg and [[Hessisches Staatstheater Wiesbaden]].\n\nFor some years, del Valle was engaged as the Principal Tenor at the [[Staatstheater Darmstadt]],<ref>Orpheus Oper International, Rittersstrasse 11, D-10969 Berlin, Heft 5, June 2001: Thema: \"Ten\u00f6re!\"  A 4848 E</ref> at the invitation of [[Marc Albrecht]].<ref>''Frankfurter Rundschau'', August 3, 2004.</ref><ref name=\"auto\">\"Wer? Wann? Was?\", ''Darmst\u00e4dter Echo'', October 9, 2001.</ref> His career followed by performances in Israel, Korea, Catania, Sydney (recording [[Elgar]]'s [[The Dream of Gerontius]] at the [[Sydney Opera House]]), Lisbon and Prague.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\nHe has collaborated with some of the most notable conductors in the world including, [[Vladimir Jurowski]], [[Ralf Otto]], [[Asher Fisch]],  [[Anton Guadagno]], [[Roberto Paternostro]], [[Claudio Abbado]], [[Eduardo Mata]], [[Benjamin Zander]], [[Isaac Karabtchevsky]], [[Peter Maag]], [[John DeMain]], [[Carl St. Clair]], [[JoAnn Falletta]], [[John Nelson (conductor)|John Nelson]], [[Dan Ettinger]], [[Carlo Maria Giulini]],  [[Alexander Lazarev]]. [[Stefan Blunier]], [[Philippe Entremont]], [[Joseph Rescigno]] and [[Richard Bonynge]].<ref>\"Malen wie ein Vogel, der sein Lied Pfeift\" [http://www.mathilde-frauenzeitung.de/mh67malenwie.html - Interview] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928205040/http://www.mathilde-frauenzeitung.de/mh67malenwie.html|date=September 28, 2007}}</ref><ref>[[:de:Deutsche Nationalbibliothek]]</ref><ref>* {{DNB-Portal|124953328}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003 his portrait was realised by [[Ricarda Jaccobi]] prot\u00e9g\u00e9 of [[Oskar Kokoschka]].[[File:Fdvjacobi.jpg|thumb|Fernando Del Valle by Ricarda Jacobi]]On the occasion of the 150th (1854\u20132004) Anniversary of [[Santa Tecla, El Salvador]], Mr. del Valle was invited by former Salvadoran Ambassador Ernesto Rivas-Gallont to present 2 Concerts. A devotee of [[Saint Th\u00e9r\u00e8se of Lisieux]], the Tenor requested that the first performance take place on September 23, the feast-day of [[Thecla|Saint Thecla]], the [[Saint]] for whom the city is named.<ref>Eugenia Vel\u00e1squez,[metro@elsalvador.com \"Santa Tecla con 150 a\u00f1os\"], ''El Diario de Hoy'', August 9, 2004.</ref>\n\nSince 2004, due to health issues, he does not perform in large scale productions but does still work as a singer, for instance at charity events. He continues training his voice and rehearses with a piano-player to keep his repertoire in good shape.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.echo-online.de/nachrichten/kunstundkultur/Mutmacher-mit-starker-Stimme;art1161,5934680 |title=''Darmst\u00e4dter Echo'', February 20, 2015. |access-date=2015-02-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150226160442/http://www.echo-online.de/nachrichten/kunstundkultur/Mutmacher-mit-starker-Stimme;art1161,5934680 |archive-date=2015-02-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>[http://www.echo-online.de Tanz und Toene fuer fluechlings], October 21, 2015.</ref><ref>\"Freund, greift ein!\" BENEFITZKONZERT Muskier des Staatstheater Darmstadt sammeln 21,000 Euro an Spender fuer Fluechtlingshlfe.{{in lang|de}}</ref>\n\n===Health===\nIn 1995, he was diagnosed with [[Type 1 diabetes]] when he was 31 years old, and treated at [[Parkland Memorial Hospital]].<ref>''Frankfurter Rundschau'', 3 August 2004.</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/> Legally blind, he suffers from [[diabetic retinopathy]], [[glaucoma]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.icaretonometer.com/?s=fernando+del+valle&x=0&y=0|title=You searched for fernando del valle - Icaretonometer|website=Icaretonometer}}</ref> [[macular degeneration]], [[Ocular ischemic syndrome]], [[cataracts]], [[macular edema]], [[diabetic cardiomyopathy]] and [[diabetic neuropathy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.echo-online.de/nachrichten/kunstundkultur/Mutmacher-mit-starker-Stimme;art1161,5934680|title=Mutmacher mit starker Stimme|first=Echo Zeitungen|last=GmbH|access-date=2015-02-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150226160442/http://www.echo-online.de/nachrichten/kunstundkultur/Mutmacher-mit-starker-Stimme;art1161,5934680|archive-date=2015-02-26|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Roles sung on stage==\n'''[[Bizet]]'''\n*''[[Carmen]]'' - Don Jos\u00e9\n*''[[Les p\u00eacheurs de perles]]'' - Nadir\n\n'''[[Boito]]'''\n*''[[Mefistofele]]'' - Faust\n'''[[Donizetti]]'''\n*''[[L'elisir d'amore]]'' - Nemorino\n*''[[Lucia di Lammermoor]]'' - Edgardo\n*''[[Lucrezia Borgia]]'' - Rustighello\n'''[[Umberto Giordano|Giordano]]'''\n*''[[Andrea Ch\u00e9nier]]'' - Title role\n'''[[Ant\u00f4nio Carlos Gomes|Gomes]]'''\n*''[[Fosca (opera)|Fosca]]'' - Paolo\n*''[[Salvator Rosa]]'' - Title role\n\n'''[[Gounod]]'''\n*''[[Faust (opera)|Faust]]'' - Title role\n'''[[Andr\u00e9 Ernest Modeste Gr\u00e9try]]'''\n*''[[Z\u00e9mire et Azor]]'' - Azor\n\n'''[[Lehar]]'''\n*''[[Die lustige Witwe]]'' - Camille de Rosillon\n'''[[Leoncavallo]]'''\n*''[[Pagliacci]]'' - Canio\n'''[[Pietro Mascagni|Mascagni]]'''\n*''[[Cavalleria rusticana]]'' - Turiddu\n\n'''[[Massenet]]''' \n*''[[Manon]]'' - des Grieux\n*''[[Werther]]'' - Title role\n\n'''[[Mozart]]'''\n*''[[Die Zauberfl\u00f6te]]'' - Tamino\n'''[[Ponchielli]]'''\n*''[[La Gioconda (opera)|La Gioconda]]'' - Enzo\n'''[[Jacques Offenbach]]'''\n*''[[Les contes d'Hoffmann]]'' - Title role\n\n'''[[Puccini]]'''\n*''[[La fanciulla del West]]'' - Dick Johnson\n*''[[Tosca]]'' - Cavaradossi\n*''[[La rondine]]'' - Prunier\n*''[[La boh\u00e8me]]'' - Rodolfo\n*''[[Madama Butterfly]]'' - B.F. Pinkerton\n*''[[Manon Lescaut]]'' - des Grieux\n*''[[Le Villi]]'' - Roberto\n'''[[Johann Strauss II|Johann Strauss]]'''\n*''[[Die Fledermaus]]'' - Alfred, Eisenstein\n\n'''[[Richard Strauss|Strauss]]'''\n*''[[Salome (opera)|Salome]]'' - Narraboth\n*''[[Die Frau ohne Schatten]]'' -  Die Stimme des J\u00fcnglings\n\n'''[[Verdi]]''' \n*''[[Attila (opera)|Attila]]'' - Foresto\n*''[[I Lombardi alla prima crociata]]'' - Oronte\n*''[[La traviata]]'' - Alfredo Germont\n*''[[Macbeth (opera)|Macbeth]]'' - Macduff\n*''[[Nabucco]]'' - Ismaele\n*''[[Rigoletto]]'' - Duca di Mantua\n*''[[Falstaff]]'' - Fenton/Bardolfo\n*''[[Simon Boccanegra]]'' - Gabriele Adorno\n*''[[Messa da Requiem]]''\n\n'''[[Richard Wagner]]'''\n*''[[Tannh\u00e4user (opera)|Tannhauser]]'' - Walther von der Vogelweide\n*''[[The Flying Dutchman (opera)|The Flying Dutchman]]'' - Steuermann\n*''[[Tristan und Isolde]]'' - Stimme eines jungen Seemanns\n\n==Discography==\n* [[Anton\u00edn Dvo\u0159\u00e1k]] [[Stabat Mater]], op. 58, Akademischer Chor Zuerich, Universitaetsorchester Innsbruck, December 2010\n* [[Elgar]]'s ''[[The Dream of Gerontius]], [[Sydney Philharmonia Choirs]], recorded live at [[Sydney Opera House]], June 13, 2010\n* [[Beethoven]]'s [[Symphony No. 9 (Beethoven)|Symphony No. 9]], Orchestra Sinfonica di Roma, La Vecchia, {{ASIN|B003916FH6}}  (Allegro)\n* [[Ant\u00f4nio Carlos Gomes]]'s [[Salvator Rosa (opera)]], Patrick Shelly, Dorset Opera and the Musicians Union of Great Britain, {{ASIN|B000G16FG6}}<ref>https://books.google.de/books?id=sJjHbguwR1oC&pg=RA1-PA7&lpg=RA1-PA7&dq=fernando+del+valle+TENOR&source=bl&ots=QV3hQHHrr7&sig=0PWTdWgtnHuk8mOEyiFYD-6e2bY&hl=de&sa=X&ei=TIobVaC-OMTnarLPgogJ&ved=0CEAQ6AEwBjgK#v=onepage&q=fernando%20del%20valle%20TENOR&f=false seite 6,</ref>\n* \"Fernando del Valle\" Arias, Eraldo Salmieri The [[New Symphony Orchestra]] of [[Sofia]] Producer: Michael A. Skinner, {{ASIN|B00004RKGZ}}\n* \"Magna res est amor\", [[:de:Martin Sander|Martin Sander]], Organ, {{ASIN|B00008ZAZD}}\n* [[Verdi]]'s ''[[Requiem (Verdi)|Requiem]]'', John Nelson with Staatsphilharmonie Rheinland-Pfalz, {{ASIN|B00IT6SHTA}} (Naxos)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090206180032/http://fernandodelvalle.com/ Fernando del Valle: The Official Web Site]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L_LDnojHjr4 Fernando del Valle in an excerpt from ''Carmen'']\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090306174226/http://sfopera.com/merolaalumni.asp Merola Opera Program Alumni]\n*[http://www.tulane.edu/~music/people/alumni.html Tulane University Alumni]\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Opera}}{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Del Valle, Fernando}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American people of Salvadoran descent]]\n[[Category:American operatic tenors]]\n[[Category:Musicians from New Orleans]]\n[[Category:Brother Martin High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Tulane University alumni]]\n[[Category:American people of Hungarian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Southern Methodist University alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century American opera singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American opera singers]]\n[[Category:People with type 1 diabetes]]\n[[Category:Singers from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:20th-century male singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n[[Category:Classical musicians from Louisiana]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n|name            = Fernando del Valle \n|image           = TENOR_FERNANDO_DEL_VALLE_ONSTAGE.jpg\n|image_size      = 220\n|caption         = del Valle in 2010\n|background      = solo_singer\n|birth_name      = Brian Stephen Skinner\n|alias           = \n|birth_date      = {{birth date|1964|02|28}}\n|birth_place     = [[New Orleans|New Orleans, Louisiana]], United States\n|death_date      = \n|death_place     = \n|instrument      = [[Tenor]]\n|genre           = [[Opera]]\n|occupation      = Opera singer\n|years_active    = \n|label           = \n}}\n\n'''Fernando del Valle''' (n\u00e9 Brian Stephen Skinner; February 28, 1964) is an American [[opera]]tic [[tenor]]. He is the son of Edward King Skinner II, a [[Korean War]] veteran<ref name=\"tributes.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tributes.com/show/Edward-King-Skinner-86579321|title=Edward Skinner Obituary - Metairie, Louisiana - Lake Lawn Metairie Funeral Home and Cemeteries|website=www.tributes.com}}</ref> and Concha Marina Mel\u00e9ndez del Valle. The grandson of Aranka Bischitz great great granddaughter of Baroness [[Johanna Bischitz von Heves]] and cousin  of [[Hungary|Hungarian]] [[radiochemist]] and [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry]] laureate [[George de Hevesy]] and Fernando Melendez del Valle-Parker. He is the nephew of the Architect [[:de:Manuel Roberto Mel\u00e9ndez Bischitz|Manuel Roberto Mel\u00e9ndez Bischitz]].\n\n==Ancestry==\nHe took the name del Valle in honour of his grandfather, Fernando Mel\u00e9ndez del Valle,<ref>[http://www.elsalvador.com/mwedh/nota/nota_completa.asp?idCat=6461&idArt=5301703] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141208000341/http://www.elsalvador.com/mwedh/nota/nota_completa.asp?idCat=6461&idArt=5301703 |date=2014-12-08 }}</ref> who was also a tenor and diplomat for [[El Salvador]] at the consulate of El Salvador in New Orleans.<ref>\"Santa Tecla, Cronolog\u00eda\" {{ISBN|99923-0-141-4}} Recopilada por Dr. Juan Jos\u00e9 Contreras Callejas, Mauricio Alvarado Cea Campo, \u00c1ngela Margarita Alvarado: Consejo National para la Cultura y el Arte, CONCULTURA, San Salvador 2004: Page 14, \"El Diario de Hoy\", November 30, 1985.</ref><ref>''New Orleans Magazine'', July 1999.</ref>\n\nHe is the great-great-grandson of [[Andr\u00e9s del Valle]], President of El Salvador in 1876<ref>Cuisine, Texas: a multiethnic feast, page 258, Joanne Smith, [[University of Texas Press]] (September 1, 2010), {{ISBN|978-0292728516}}</ref> and a direct descendant of Colonel [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda San Mart\u00edn]], [[President of El Salvador]] (1854\u201356) and founder of [[Santa Tecla, El Salvador]].<ref>[http://archive.laprensa.com.sv/20040822/opinion/opinion1.asp \"La distinguida genealog\u00eda de los San Mart\u00edn\"], ''Prensa Grafica'', August 22, 2004.</ref><ref>Morena Azucena, [http://www.elsalvador.com \"Un tenor l\u00edrico con ra\u00edces tecle\u00f1as\"], elsalvador.com, September 22, 2004, pg. 106</ref><ref>Gobernantes de El Salvador, Maria y Freddy Leistenschneider, 1980, pg. 137 (A. del Valle) & pg. 97 (J.M. San Martin) Publicaciones Del MinisterIo Del Interior, Imprenta Nacional, San Salvador, El Salvador.</ref>\n\nHe is the grandson of the Honorable Judge Robert J. Skinner,<ref>Gary Krist, ''Empire of Sin'', New York Times Sunday Book Review, November 6, 2014.</ref><ref name=\"tributes.com\"/> former recorder and treasurer (for the City of New Orleans), a regimental sergeant-major in [[World War One]], and the great grandson of Judge Edward King Skinner, who served on the city, criminal and civil district court benches, successively, over a total period of 52 years<ref>John C. Kelly, \"R.J. Skinner Taken by Death\", ''The New Orleans Item'', July 18, 1949.</ref><ref>Library Archives Analyst II, ''The Times-Picayune''.</ref><ref>Thomas K. Griffin, \"Skinner's Ward is on the Way\", ''The Times-Picayune'' Library Archives.</ref>\n\nIn 1880, he was appointed to first district court after the [[American Civil War|Civil War]]. A year after his retirement attorneys gave civil district court a portrait in oils of Judge Skinner.<ref>'E.K. Skinner retired Judge of Civil Court Dies\" The Times Picayune/New Orleans States Volume C---NO. 134, New Orleans, Sunday, June 7, 1936, pg. 6</ref>\n\nThe portrait by John Paul Parker, was presented to the court by United States Attorney Rene A. Viosca, who was then president of the New Orleans Bar Association.<ref>'E.K. Skinner retired Judge of Civil Court Dies\" The Times Picayune/New Orleans States Volume C---NO. 134, New Orleans, Sunday, June 7, 1936, Pages 1 and 6</ref><ref>\"Biographical and  Historical Memoirs of Louisiana\", Volume 2, pp. 388-89, Goodspeed Publishing Company, Chicago, 1892.</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nHe was born in [[New Orleans]].<ref>Richard Siklos, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk \"New Orleans: \"Big year for the Big Easy\"], January 17, 2003.</ref> A graduate of [[Brother Martin High School]], he received his Bachelor of Fine Arts from [[Tulane University]] as the recipient of the Treville Scholarship in Voice, and the Artists Diploma from [[Southern Methodist University]] as the Haggar Scholar.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\nAs a winner of the Dallas Opera Guild Vocal Competition he was awarded a Career Grant from The [[Dallas Opera]], the winner of the Stewart Award, the [[Austin Lyric Opera]] Vocal Competition, the [[Fort Worth Opera]] Competition and the Vocal Competition of the [[San Antonio Opera]] judged by [[Evelyn Lear]] and [[Richard Gaddes]].{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\nHe is an alumnus of the [[San Francisco Opera]]'s [[Merola Opera Program]] where he studied under the direction of [[Patrick Summers]] in 1992 and 1993. He later won the \"Bel Canto\" competition of Chicago and subsequently relocated to Italy where he studied under [[Carlo Bergonzi]] and, later, [[Thomas Hayward (tenor)|Thomas Hayward]] and [[Nicolai Gedda]].{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\n===Early years===\nDel Valle made his operatic debut at the age of seventeen (1981), as the First Shepherd in [[John Blow]]'s ''[[Venus and Adonis (Blow)]]'', at [[Loyola University New Orleans|Loyola University]] followed by roles in [[La rondine]], conducted by [[Maurice Peress]], ''[[Brigadoon]]'', ''[[Shenandoah (musical)|Shenandoah]]'' and ''[[The Merry Widow]]''.\n\nThe next year, after the intervention and advice of his [[Tulane]] professor, [[Deborah Drattell]], he became tenor soloist in Bach's \"St Matthew Passion\" with the New Orleans Philharmonic-Symphony Orchestra, [[Andrew Massey (conductor)|Andrew Massey]], conducting.  In 1986, he made his Boston debut in that composer's ''Christmas Oratorio'' in [[Jordan Hall]] as the winner of the Boston Premiere Ensembles Young Artist Competition. The following spring, his New York debut took place at [[Alice Tully Hall]], [[Lincoln Center]], with the Beethoven Society of New York.\n\nHe continued his career as a concert tenor with a repertoire that included Beethoven's ''[[Missa Solemnis (Beethoven)|Missa Solemnis]]'', and the Requiems of Verdi, [[Britten]] and [[Lloyd Webber]]. The tenor's [[Carnegie Hall]] debut occurred in 1993, with Mozart's \"Great\" Mass in C minor with the [[American Symphony Orchestra]].  He performed the tenor solos in [[George Frideric Handel]]'s ''Messiah'' for the [[Dallas Symphony Orchestra]], at the [[Morton H. Meyerson Symphony Center]] in 1994.  He made his European debut in 1995, singing in Beethoven's [[Symphony No. 9 (Beethoven)|Symphony No. 9]] with the [[Orchestra Sinfonica di Milano Giuseppe Verdi]].\n\nDel Valle's European operatic debut took place with the role of \"Don Jos\u00e9\" in the Hugo de Ana production of ''[[Carmen]]'' at the Teatro Comunale di [[Treviso]] under the vocal direction of [[Regina Resnik]] and conducted by [[Peter Maag]]. In 1996, he appeared as Rodolfo in ''[[La boh\u00e8me]]'', at the [[Teatro dell'Opera di Roma]], [[Vladimir Jurowski]], conducting.\n\n===1997\u2013present===\nIn 1997, del Valle appeared as 'don Jos\u00e9' at the Gran [[Teatro La Fenice]] in Venice, [[Isaac Karabtchevsky]], conducting 'Pinkerton' in ''Madama Butterfly'' with the [[Palm Beach Opera]], [[Anton Guadagno]], conducting and 'Faust' in [[Colmar]], France. He made his German debut in 1998 as 'Rodolfo' with the [[Frankfurt Opera]], under the direction of the venerated [[pedagogue]]/conductor, [[Klauspeter Seibel]], immediately following he appeared to critical acclaim,<ref>[[Andrew Porter (music critic)|Andrew Porter]], ''[[Financial Times]]'', October 26, 1998.<br>\"This ''Fosca'' was Wexford at its best. It brought forward a tenor of uncommon merit: del Valle was as firm as Domingo in his pure, true utterance but also able and eager, Bergonzi-wise, to \"melt\" from note to note in shapely phrases. (Caruso's splendour ''plus'' Gigli's charm make a good model)\"</ref><ref>[[Rodney Milnes]], ''[[The Times]]'', October 28, 1998.<br>\"....an exciting tenor, especially at the top of the register, who can shape a phrase with real sensitivity.\"</ref> at the [[Wexford Festival]] in Ireland as 'Paolo' in [[Fosca (opera)]] by [[Ant\u00f4nio Carlos Gomes]]. A series of important engagements followed, and since 1999, del Valle has appeared around the world, including performances in Frankfurt [[Alte Oper]], [[Strasbourg]] (Beethoven 9th Symphony, op. 125, with [[John Storgards]] conducting), Maastricht, [[Deutsche Oper am Rhein]], [[Theater Augsburg]], [[Tonhalle D\u00fcsseldorf]], [[Deutsche Oper Berlin]], [[Theater Dortmund]], [[Teatro Carlo Felice]], Bremen, Bergen, Costa Rica, Munich [[Gasteig]], [[Finnish National Opera]], Helsinki, [[Belo Horizonte]] in Brazil, the [[HIFA]] Festival in [[Harare|Harare, Zimbabwe]],<ref>Maxwell Sibanda, \"Zimbabwe: International Acts Set to Flavour Hifa\", ''The Harare Daily News'', April 29, 2003.</ref> [[Malm\u00f6, Sweden]], [[New Symphony Orchestra|New Symphony Orchestra of Sofia, Bulgaria]], [[Teatro Petruzzelli]] di [[Bari]], [[Torino]], [[Baveno]], Inaugural concert of the [[Umberto Giordano]] Festival with the [[RAI National Symphony Orchestra]], [[National Theatre Mannheim]], [[Badisches Staatstheater Karlsruhe]], [[Staatstheater Kassel]], Hamburg and [[Hessisches Staatstheater Wiesbaden]].\n\nFor some years, del Valle was engaged as the Principal Tenor at the [[Staatstheater Darmstadt]],<ref>Orpheus Oper International, Rittersstrasse 11, D-10969 Berlin, Heft 5, June 2001: Thema: \"Ten\u00f6re!\"  A 4848 E</ref> at the invitation of [[Marc Albrecht]].<ref>''Frankfurter Rundschau'', August 3, 2004.</ref><ref name=\"auto\">\"Wer? Wann? Was?\", ''Darmst\u00e4dter Echo'', October 9, 2001.</ref> His career followed by performances in Israel, Korea, Catania, Sydney (recording [[Elgar]]'s [[The Dream of Gerontius]] at the [[Sydney Opera House]]), Lisbon and Prague.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\nHe has collaborated with some of the most notable conductors in the world including, [[Vladimir Jurowski]], [[Ralf Otto]], [[Asher Fisch]],  [[Anton Guadagno]], [[Roberto Paternostro]], [[Claudio Abbado]], [[Eduardo Mata]], [[Benjamin Zander]], [[Isaac Karabtchevsky]], [[Peter Maag]], [[John DeMain]], [[Carl St. Clair]], [[JoAnn Falletta]], [[John Nelson (conductor)|John Nelson]], [[Dan Ettinger]], [[Carlo Maria Giulini]],  [[Alexander Lazarev]]. [[Stefan Blunier]], [[Philippe Entremont]], [[Joseph Rescigno]] and [[Richard Bonynge]].<ref>\"Malen wie ein Vogel, der sein Lied Pfeift\" [http://www.mathilde-frauenzeitung.de/mh67malenwie.html - Interview] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928205040/http://www.mathilde-frauenzeitung.de/mh67malenwie.html|date=September 28, 2007}}</ref><ref>[[:de:Deutsche Nationalbibliothek]]</ref><ref>* {{DNB-Portal|124953328}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003 his portrait was realised by [[Ricarda Jaccobi]] prot\u00e9g\u00e9 of [[Oskar Kokoschka]]. On the occasion of the 150th (1854\u20132004) Anniversary of [[Santa Tecla, El Salvador]], Mr. del Valle was invited by former Salvadoran Ambassador Ernesto Rivas-Gallont to present 2 Concerts. A devotee of [[Saint Th\u00e9r\u00e8se of Lisieux]], the Tenor requested that the first performance take place on September 23, the feast-day of [[Thecla|Saint Thecla]], the [[Saint]] for whom the city is named.<ref>Eugenia Vel\u00e1squez,[metro@elsalvador.com \"Santa Tecla con 150 a\u00f1os\"], ''El Diario de Hoy'', August 9, 2004.</ref>\n\nSince 2004, due to health issues, he does not perform in large scale productions but does still work as a singer, for instance at charity events. He continues training his voice and rehearses with a piano-player to keep his repertoire in good shape.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.echo-online.de/nachrichten/kunstundkultur/Mutmacher-mit-starker-Stimme;art1161,5934680 |title=''Darmst\u00e4dter Echo'', February 20, 2015. |access-date=2015-02-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150226160442/http://www.echo-online.de/nachrichten/kunstundkultur/Mutmacher-mit-starker-Stimme;art1161,5934680 |archive-date=2015-02-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>[http://www.echo-online.de Tanz und Toene fuer fluechlings], October 21, 2015.</ref><ref>\"Freund, greift ein!\" BENEFITZKONZERT Muskier des Staatstheater Darmstadt sammeln 21,000 Euro an Spender fuer Fluechtlingshlfe.{{in lang|de}}</ref>\n\n===Health===\nIn 1995, he was diagnosed with [[Type 1 diabetes]] when he was 31 years old, and treated at [[Parkland Memorial Hospital]].<ref>''Frankfurter Rundschau'', 3 August 2004.</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/> Legally blind, he suffers from [[diabetic retinopathy]], [[glaucoma]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.icaretonometer.com/?s=fernando+del+valle&x=0&y=0|title=You searched for fernando del valle - Icaretonometer|website=Icaretonometer}}</ref> [[macular degeneration]], [[Ocular ischemic syndrome]], [[cataracts]], [[macular edema]], [[diabetic cardiomyopathy]] and [[diabetic neuropathy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.echo-online.de/nachrichten/kunstundkultur/Mutmacher-mit-starker-Stimme;art1161,5934680|title=Mutmacher mit starker Stimme|first=Echo Zeitungen|last=GmbH|access-date=2015-02-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150226160442/http://www.echo-online.de/nachrichten/kunstundkultur/Mutmacher-mit-starker-Stimme;art1161,5934680|archive-date=2015-02-26|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Roles sung on stage==\n'''[[Bizet]]'''\n*''[[Carmen]]'' - Don Jos\u00e9\n*''[[Les p\u00eacheurs de perles]]'' - Nadir\n\n'''[[Boito]]'''\n*''[[Mefistofele]]'' - Faust\n'''[[Donizetti]]'''\n*''[[L'elisir d'amore]]'' - Nemorino\n*''[[Lucia di Lammermoor]]'' - Edgardo\n*''[[Lucrezia Borgia]]'' - Rustighello\n'''[[Umberto Giordano|Giordano]]'''\n*''[[Andrea Ch\u00e9nier]]'' - Title role\n'''[[Ant\u00f4nio Carlos Gomes|Gomes]]'''\n*''[[Fosca (opera)|Fosca]]'' - Paolo\n*''[[Salvator Rosa]]'' - Title role\n\n'''[[Gounod]]'''\n*''[[Faust (opera)|Faust]]'' - Title role\n'''[[Andr\u00e9 Ernest Modeste Gr\u00e9try]]'''\n*''[[Z\u00e9mire et Azor]]'' - Azor\n\n'''[[Lehar]]'''\n*''[[Die lustige Witwe]]'' - Camille de Rosillon\n'''[[Leoncavallo]]'''\n*''[[Pagliacci]]'' - Canio\n'''[[Pietro Mascagni|Mascagni]]'''\n*''[[Cavalleria rusticana]]'' - Turiddu\n\n'''[[Massenet]]''' \n*''[[Manon]]'' - des Grieux\n*''[[Werther]]'' - Title role\n\n'''[[Mozart]]'''\n*''[[Die Zauberfl\u00f6te]]'' - Tamino\n'''[[Ponchielli]]'''\n*''[[La Gioconda (opera)|La Gioconda]]'' - Enzo\n'''[[Jacques Offenbach]]'''\n*''[[Les contes d'Hoffmann]]'' - Title role\n\n'''[[Puccini]]'''\n*''[[La fanciulla del West]]'' - Dick Johnson\n*''[[Tosca]]'' - Cavaradossi\n*''[[La rondine]]'' - Prunier\n*''[[La boh\u00e8me]]'' - Rodolfo\n*''[[Madama Butterfly]]'' - B.F. Pinkerton\n*''[[Manon Lescaut]]'' - des Grieux\n*''[[Le Villi]]'' - Roberto\n'''[[Johann Strauss II|Johann Strauss]]'''\n*''[[Die Fledermaus]]'' - Alfred, Eisenstein\n\n'''[[Richard Strauss|Strauss]]'''\n*''[[Salome (opera)|Salome]]'' - Narraboth\n*''[[Die Frau ohne Schatten]]'' -  Die Stimme des J\u00fcnglings\n\n'''[[Verdi]]''' \n*''[[Attila (opera)|Attila]]'' - Foresto\n*''[[I Lombardi alla prima crociata]]'' - Oronte\n*''[[La traviata]]'' - Alfredo Germont\n*''[[Macbeth (opera)|Macbeth]]'' - Macduff\n*''[[Nabucco]]'' - Ismaele\n*''[[Rigoletto]]'' - Duca di Mantua\n*''[[Falstaff]]'' - Fenton/Bardolfo\n*''[[Simon Boccanegra]]'' - Gabriele Adorno\n*''[[Messa da Requiem]]''\n\n'''[[Richard Wagner]]'''\n*''[[Tannh\u00e4user (opera)|Tannhauser]]'' - Walther von der Vogelweide\n*''[[The Flying Dutchman (opera)|The Flying Dutchman]]'' - Steuermann\n*''[[Tristan und Isolde]]'' - Stimme eines jungen Seemanns\n\n==Discography==\n* [[Anton\u00edn Dvo\u0159\u00e1k]] [[Stabat Mater]], op. 58, Akademischer Chor Zuerich, Universitaetsorchester Innsbruck, December 2010\n* [[Elgar]]'s ''[[The Dream of Gerontius]], [[Sydney Philharmonia Choirs]], recorded live at [[Sydney Opera House]], June 13, 2010\n* [[Beethoven]]'s [[Symphony No. 9 (Beethoven)|Symphony No. 9]], Orchestra Sinfonica di Roma, La Vecchia, {{ASIN|B003916FH6}}  (Allegro)\n* [[Ant\u00f4nio Carlos Gomes]]'s [[Salvator Rosa (opera)]], Patrick Shelly, Dorset Opera and the Musicians Union of Great Britain, {{ASIN|B000G16FG6}}<ref>https://books.google.de/books?id=sJjHbguwR1oC&pg=RA1-PA7&lpg=RA1-PA7&dq=fernando+del+valle+TENOR&source=bl&ots=QV3hQHHrr7&sig=0PWTdWgtnHuk8mOEyiFYD-6e2bY&hl=de&sa=X&ei=TIobVaC-OMTnarLPgogJ&ved=0CEAQ6AEwBjgK#v=onepage&q=fernando%20del%20valle%20TENOR&f=false seite 6,</ref>\n* \"Fernando del Valle\" Arias, Eraldo Salmieri The [[New Symphony Orchestra]] of [[Sofia]] Producer: Michael A. Skinner, {{ASIN|B00004RKGZ}}\n* \"Magna res est amor\", [[:de:Martin Sander|Martin Sander]], Organ, {{ASIN|B00008ZAZD}}\n* [[Verdi]]'s ''[[Requiem (Verdi)|Requiem]]'', John Nelson with Staatsphilharmonie Rheinland-Pfalz, {{ASIN|B00IT6SHTA}} (Naxos)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090206180032/http://fernandodelvalle.com/ Fernando del Valle: The Official Web Site]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L_LDnojHjr4 Fernando del Valle in an excerpt from ''Carmen'']\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090306174226/http://sfopera.com/merolaalumni.asp Merola Opera Program Alumni]\n*[http://www.tulane.edu/~music/people/alumni.html Tulane University Alumni]\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Opera}}{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Del Valle, Fernando}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American people of Salvadoran descent]]\n[[Category:American operatic tenors]]\n[[Category:Musicians from New Orleans]]\n[[Category:Brother Martin High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Tulane University alumni]]\n[[Category:American people of Hungarian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Southern Methodist University alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century American opera singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American opera singers]]\n[[Category:People with type 1 diabetes]]\n[[Category:Singers from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:20th-century male singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n[[Category:Classical musicians from Louisiana]]\n", "name_user": "Tenorbear", "label": "safe", "comment": "added portrait in oil by the recently deceased artist, former student of Oscar Kokoschka, Ricarda Jacobi", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fernando_del_Valle"}
{"title_page": "List of international trips made by Mike Pompeo as United States Secretary of State", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n[[File:Mike Pompeo and Xi Jinping.jpg|thumb|Secretary of State [[Mike Pompeo]] with Chinese president [[Xi Jinping]] in [[Beijing]], June 2018]]\n[[File:Secretary Pompeo Meets With Japanese Prime Minister (43219435102).jpg|thumb|Secretary of State Mike Pompeo with Japanese prime minister [[Shinz\u014d Abe]] in Tokyo, July 2018]]\n[[File:Secretary Pompeo and Chairman Kim Attend Working Lunch in Pyongyang (44430203414).jpg|thumb|Mike Pompeo with North Korean leader [[Kim Jong-un]] in [[Pyongyang]], October 2018]]\n[[File:Secretary Pompeo Meets With President Moon in Seoul (31282273478).jpg|thumb|Secretary of State Mike Pompeo with South Korean president [[Moon Jae-in]] in [[Seoul]], October 2018]]\n\nThis is a list of international visits undertaken by [[Mike Pompeo]] (in office 2018\u2013present)<ref name=\"officeofthehistorian\" /> while serving as the [[United States Secretary of State|United States secretary of state]]. The list includes both private travel and [[Official visit|official state visits]]. The list includes only foreign travel which the secretaries of state have made during their tenure in the position.<ref name=\"officeofthehistorian\">{{cite web|url=https://history.state.gov/departmenthistory/travels/secretary  |title=Travels Abroad of the Secretary of State |publisher=Office of the Historian, Bureau of Public Affairs United States Department of State}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n|+\n|-\n!\n! style=\"width: 13%;\" |Country\n! style=\"width: 12%;\" |Locations\n! style=\"width: 55%;\" |Details\n! style=\"width: 20%;\" |Dates\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" |1\n|{{flag|Belgium}}\n|[[Brussels]]\n|Attended a [[NATO]] foreign ministers\u2019 meeting.\n|April 26\u201327, 2018\n|-\n|{{flag|Saudi Arabia}}\n|[[Riyadh]]\n|Met with [[Saudi Arabia|Saudi]] foreign minister [[Adel al-Jubeir]].\n|April 28\u201329, 2018\n|-\n|{{flag|Israel}}\n|[[Tel Aviv]]\n|Met with [[Israel]]i prime minister [[Benjamin Netanyahu]].\n|April 29, 2018\n|-\n|{{flag|Jordan}}\n|[[Amman]]\n|Met with [[Abdullah II of Jordan|King Abdullah II]] and Foreign Minister [[Ayman Safadi]].  Also met with Japanese foreign minister [[Taro Kono]].<ref name=\"Pompeo\">{{cite web|title=Travel to Belgium, Saudi Arabia, Israel, Jordan, April 26-30, 2018|url=https://www.state.gov/secretary/travel/2018/t6/index.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180428093305/https://www.state.gov/secretary/travel/2018/t6/index.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=28 April 2018|publisher=US State Department|accessdate=21 October 2018|language=en}} {{PD-notice}}</ref>\n|April 30, 2018\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" |2\n|{{flag|North Korea}}\n|[[Pyongyang]]\n|Met with Chairman [[Kim Jong-un]] and other North Korean government officials. Also secured the release of three Americans.<ref name=\"Pompeo2\">{{cite web|title=Travel to Japan and North Korea, May 8-9, 2018\n|url=https://www.state.gov/secretary/travel/2018/t7/index.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180509042044/https://www.state.gov/secretary/travel/2018/t7/index.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=9 May 2018|publisher=US State Department|accessdate=21 October 2018|language=en}} {{PD-notice}}</ref>\n|May 8\u20139, 2018\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" |3\n|{{flag|Canada}}\n|[[La Malbaie]]\n|Accompanied President [[Donald Trump|Trump]] to the [[44th G7 summit|G-7 meetings]].\n|June 9, 2018\n|-\n|{{flag|Singapore}}\n|[[Singapore]]\n|Participated in the president's [[2018 North Korea\u2013United States Singapore Summit|summit]] with North Korean leader [[Kim Jong-un]] and bilateral events with Singaporean prime minister [[Lee Hsien Loong]].\n|June 10\u201313, 2018\n|-\n|{{flag|South Korea}}\n|[[Seoul]]\n|Met with senior Korean and Japanese officials to discuss the U.S.\u2013Republic of Korea alliance, the U.S.\u2013Japan alliance, and next steps in a shared approach to North Korea.\n|June 13\u201314, 2018\n|-\n|{{flag|China}}\n|[[Beijing]]\n|Met with Chinese officials on bilateral, regional, and global issues that affect both countries.<ref name=\"Pompeo3\">{{cite web|title=Travel to Canada, Singapore, South Korea, and China, June 9-14, 2018\n|url=https://www.state.gov/secretary/travel/2018/t9/index.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180609230703/https://www.state.gov/secretary/travel/2018/t9/index.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=9 June 2018|publisher=US State Department|accessdate=21 October 2018|language=en}} {{PD-notice}}</ref>\n|June 14, 2018\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\" |4\n|{{flag|North Korea}}\n|[[Pyongyang]]\n|Continued consultations and implementation of the forward progress made by President Trump and Chairman Kim in Singapore.\n|July 5\u20137, 2018\n|-\n|{{flag|Japan}}\n|[[Tokyo]]\n|Met with Japanese and South Korean leaders to discuss our shared commitment to the final, fully verified denuclearization of the DPRK, as well as other bilateral and regional issues.\n|July 7\u20138, 2018\n|-\n|{{flag|Vietnam}}\n|[[Hanoi]]\n|Met with senior Vietnamese officials to discuss our shared commitment to the final, fully verified denuclearization of the DPRK and other bilateral and regional issues.\n|July 8\u20139, 2018\n|-\n|{{flag|Afghanistan}}\n|[[Kabul]]\n|Met with Afghan officials.\n|July 9, 2018\n|-\n|{{flag|United Arab Emirates}}\n|[[Abu Dhabi]]\n|Met with UAE leaders to discuss ways to further strengthen the U.S.\u2013UAE partnership.\n|July 9\u201310, 2018\n|-\n|{{flag|Belgium}}\n|[[Brussels]]\n|Accompanied President [[Donald Trump|Trump]] to the [[2018 Brussels summit|NATO Summit]] and also participated in the U.S.\u2013EU Energy Council and co-hosted a meeting of foreign ministers of the Global Coalition to Defeat ISIS.<ref name=\"Pompeo4\">{{cite web|title=Travel to Pyongyang, Tokyo, Hanoi, Kabul, Abu Dhabi, and Brussels, July 5-12, 2018\n|url=https://www.state.gov/secretary/travel/2018/t10/index.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709054926/https://www.state.gov/secretary/travel/2018/t10/index.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=9 July 2018|publisher=US State Department|accessdate=21 October 2018|language=en}} {{PD-notice}}</ref>\n|July 10\u201312, 2018\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" |5\n|{{flag|Mexico}}\n|[[Mexico City]]\n|Met with President [[Enrique Pe\u00f1a Nieto]], Foreign Secretary [[Luis Videgaray Caso]], and President-elect [[Andres Manuel Lopez Obrador]].<ref name=\"Pompeo5\">{{cite web|title=Travel to Mexico, July 13, 2018\n|url=https://www.state.gov/secretary/travel/2018/t11/index.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180714045756/https://www.state.gov/secretary/travel/2018/t11/index.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=14 July 2018|publisher=US State Department|accessdate=21 October 2018|language=en}} {{PD-notice}}</ref>\n|July 13, 2018\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" |6\n|{{flag|Finland}}\n|[[Helsinki]]\n|Accompanied President [[Donald Trump|Trump]] to his [[2018 Russia\u2013United States summit|meeting]] with Russian president [[Vladimir Putin]]. Also met with Russian foreign minister [[Sergey Lavrov]] and Finnish foreign minister [[Timo Soini]], to discuss bilateral and regional issues.<ref name=\"Pompeo6\">{{cite web|title=Travel to Helsinki, July 16, 2018\n|url=https://www.state.gov/secretary/travel/2018/t12/index.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180717051653/https://www.state.gov/secretary/travel/2018/t12/index.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=17 July 2018|publisher=US State Department|accessdate=21 October 2018|language=en}} {{PD-notice}}</ref>\n|July 16, 2018\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |7\n|{{flag|Malaysia}}\n|[[Kuala Lumpur]]\n|Met with senior Malaysian officials to discuss strengthening the comprehensive partnership and advancing common security and economic interests.\n|August 1\u20133, 2018\n|-\n|{{flag|Singapore}}\n|[[Singapore]]\n|Participated in annual [[Association of Southeast Asian Nations|ASEAN]]-centered ministerial meetings.\n|August 3\u20134, 2018\n|-\n|{{flag|Indonesia}}\n|[[Jakarta]]\n|Met with senior Indonesian officials to discuss U.S.\u2013Indonesia strategic partnership.<ref name=\"Pompeo7\">{{cite web|title=Travel to Kuala Lumpur, Singapore, and Jakarta, August 1-5, 2018\n|url=https://www.state.gov/secretary/travel/2018/t13/index.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180803064333/https://www.state.gov/secretary/travel/2018/t13/index.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=3 August 2018|publisher=US State Department|accessdate=21 October 2018|language=en}} {{PD-notice}}</ref>\n|August 4\u20135, 2018\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |8\n|{{flag|Pakistan}}\n|[[Islamabad]]\n|Met with Prime Minister [[Imran Khan]], Foreign Minister [[Qureshi]], and Chief of Army Staff [[Qamar Javed Bajwa]] to discuss U.S.\u2013Pakistan bilateral relations.\n|September 5, 2018\n|-\n|{{flag|India}}\n|[[New Delhi]]\n|Participated in the inaugural U.S.\u2013India \u201c2+2\u201d dialogue and met with senior officials.<ref name=\"Pompeo8\">{{cite web|title=Travel to Pakistan and India, September 4-7, 2018\n|url=https://www.state.gov/secretary/travel/2018/t14/index.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905193851/https://www.state.gov/secretary/travel/2018/t14/index.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=5 September 2018|publisher=US State Department|accessdate=21 October 2018|language=en}} {{PD-notice}}</ref>\n|September 6, 2018\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" |9\n|{{flag|Japan}}\n|[[Tokyo]]\n|Met with Prime Minister [[Shinzo Abe]] and Foreign Minister [[Taro Kono]].\n|October 6\u20137, 2018\n|-\n|{{flag|North Korea}}\n|[[Pyongyang]]\n|Met with Chairman [[Kim Jong-un]].\n|October 7, 2018\n|-\n|{{flag|South Korea}}\n|[[Seoul]]\n|Met with President [[Moon Jae-in]] and Foreign Minister [[Kang Kyung-wha]].\n|October 7\u20138, 2018\n|-\n|{{flag|China}}\n|[[Beijing]]\n|Met with Chinese counterparts to discuss bilateral, regional, and global issues.<ref name=\"Pompeo9\">{{cite web|title=Travel to Japan, North Korea, South Korea, and China, October 6-8, 2018\n|url=https://www.state.gov/secretary/travel/2018/t16/index.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181007064307/https://www.state.gov/secretary/travel/2018/t16/index.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=7 October 2018|publisher=US State Department|accessdate=21 October 2018|language=en}} {{PD-notice}}</ref>\n|October 8, 2018\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" |10\n|{{flag|Saudi Arabia}}\n|[[Riyadh]]\n|Met with Crown Prince [[Mohammad bin Salman]] and Foreign Minister [[Adel al-Jubeir]] regarding the investigation into the disappearance of [[Jamal Khashoggi]].<ref name=\"Pompeo10\">{{cite web|title=Travel to Saudi Arabia, October 15-16, 2018\n|url=https://www.state.gov/secretary/travel/2018/t17/index.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181016143934/https://www.state.gov/secretary/travel/2018/t17/index.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=16 October 2018|publisher=US State Department|accessdate=21 October 2018|language=en}} {{PD-notice}}</ref>\n|October 15\u201317, 2018\n|-\n|{{flag|Turkey}}\n|[[Ankara]]\n|Met with Foreign Minister [[Mevl\u00fct \u00c7avu\u015fo\u011flu]] and President [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]]<ref name=\"Pompeo11\">{{cite web|title=Travel to Turkey, October 17, 2018\n|url=https://www.state.gov/secretary/travel/2018/t18/index.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181017082309/https://www.state.gov/secretary/travel/2018/t18/index.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=17 October 2018|publisher=US State Department|accessdate=21 October 2018|language=en}} {{PD-notice}}</ref>\n|October 17, 2018\n|-\n|{{flag|Panama}}\n|[[Panama City]]\n|Met with President [[Juan Carlos Varela]] and Vice President and Foreign Minister [[Isabel Saint Malo|Isabel de Saint Malo de Alvarado]] to discuss ongoing U.S.\u2013Panama collaboration on regional priorities.\n|October 18, 2018\n|-\n|{{flag|Mexico}}\n|[[Mexico City]]\n|Met with President [[Enrique Pe\u00f1a Nieto]], Foreign Secretary [[Luis Videgaray Caso]], and Foreign Secretary\u